// Unit 14: Erster Arbeitstag
// Level: B1

const UNIT_14 =
{n:14,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Erster Arbeitstag",sub:"First day at work, office culture, passive voice, relative clauses",icon:"💼",level:"B1.1",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[

// ─── Lesson 1: Der erste Morgen ───
{id:"deu_r14l1",title:"Der erste Morgen",icon:"🌅",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der erste Morgen",desc:"Verumius stands in front of his new workplace in Berlin-Mitte. He is wearing a suit. Everyone else is wearing jeans. Time to discover the German office world.",goals:["Learn 20 key workplace vocabulary words","Understand the structure of a German office","Follow Verumius through his first workday with Mia as guide"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"excited",art:"de-ber-office-exterior",trg:"Es ist Montagmorgen in Berlin-Mitte. Verumius steht vor einem modernen Bürogebäude aus Glas und Stahl. Er trägt einen Anzug. Alle anderen tragen Jeans.",src:"It is Monday morning in Berlin-Mitte. Verumius stands in front of a modern office building of glass and steel. He is wearing a suit. Everyone else is wearing jeans."},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"amused",art:"de-ber-office-entrance",trg:"Willkommen im Betrieb! Du bist etwas overdressed. Aber keine Sorge, das passiert jedem am ersten Tag.",src:"Welcome to the company! You are a bit overdressed. But no worries, that happens to everyone on the first day."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Betrieb",src:"the company, the operation",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'betreiben' (to operate). A Betrieb is any active business.\n'Im Betrieb' means at work or in operation.",example:"A: Wie lange gibt es diesen Betrieb schon?\nB: Seit zwanzig Jahren. Er wurde 2006 gegründet.\nA: Und wie viele Leute arbeiten hier?\nB: Ungefähr zweihundert im ganzen Betrieb.",exampleSrc:"A: How long has this company existed?\nB: For twenty years. It was founded in 2006.\nA: And how many people work here?\nB: About two hundred in the whole company.",funFact:"Germans distinguish Firma (legal company name), Betrieb (active operation), and Unternehmen (enterprise). A Betrieb can be a factory, an office, or a bakery. If it operates, it is a Betrieb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Abteilung",src:"the department",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Ab- (off) + teilen (to divide). A department is a 'division.'\nEvery German company is organized into Abteilungen.",example:"A: In welcher Abteilung arbeitest du?\nB: In der Marketing-Abteilung.\nA: Und wie viele Leute sind in deiner Abteilung?\nB: Wir sind zu zwölft.",exampleSrc:"A: Which department do you work in?\nB: In the marketing department.\nA: And how many people are in your department?\nB: There are twelve of us.",funFact:"Your Abteilung defines your identity at work. Germans introduce themselves by department: 'Ich bin aus der IT-Abteilung.' It is your workplace tribe."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Etage",src:"the floor, the level",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Borrowed from French. 'Erste Etage' = first floor ABOVE ground.\nGround floor is 'Erdgeschoss.'",example:"A: Auf welcher Etage ist die Kantine?\nB: Im dritten Stock, also dritte Etage.\nA: Gibt es einen Aufzug?\nB: Ja, am Ende vom Flur.",exampleSrc:"A: Which floor is the canteen on?\nB: On the third floor, so third level.\nA: Is there an elevator?\nB: Yes, at the end of the hallway.",funFact:"Germans say 'erste Etage' for the first floor ABOVE ground. Ground floor is 'Erdgeschoss.' So 'dritte Etage' equals the British third floor or the American fourth floor. Confusion guaranteed for visitors."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Flur",src:"the hallway, the corridor",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Where you overhear gossip and bump into the boss.\nAlso means 'open field' in old German.",example:"A: Wo ist das Büro von Frau Müller?\nB: Am Ende vom Flur, die letzte Tür links.\nA: Danke! Der Flur ist aber lang.\nB: Ja, wir haben eine große Etage.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is Frau Müller's office?\nB: At the end of the hallway, the last door on the left.\nA: Thanks! The hallway is quite long.\nB: Yes, we have a large floor.",funFact:"The Flur is where German office culture happens: chance encounters with the boss, overheard phone calls, and the eternal walk to the coffee kitchen. Many important decisions are made 'auf dem Flur.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Gang",src:"the corridor, the aisle",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Both a corridor AND a course of a meal.\n'Der Gang zum Kopierer' uses the same word as 'der erste Gang' (first course).",example:"A: Der Konferenzraum ist am Ende des Gangs.\nB: Welcher Gang? Es gibt hier so viele!\nA: Der Gang rechts neben der Kaffeküche.\nB: Ah, jetzt sehe ich ihn.",exampleSrc:"A: The conference room is at the end of the corridor.\nB: Which corridor? There are so many here!\nA: The corridor to the right of the coffee kitchen.\nB: Ah, now I see it.",funFact:"Gang has many meanings: corridor, aisle (in a plane), course (of a meal), gear (in a car), and gait (how you walk). Context is everything in German."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie heißt der lange Weg im Büro, an dem die Bürotüren liegen?",opts:["die Kantine","die Garderobe","der Flur","die Etage"],ans:"der Flur",hint:"The place where you walk past offices and bump into the boss. Also called Gang."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kantine",src:"the canteen, the cafeteria",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'cantina.' The company cafeteria.\nSubsidized meals, salad bars, Currywurst on Fridays.",example:"A: Wo essen die meisten zu Mittag?\nB: In der Kantine. Das Essen ist gut und günstig.\nA: Was kostet ein Mittagessen?\nB: Ungefähr vier Euro. Der Betrieb zahlt den Rest.",exampleSrc:"A: Where do most people eat lunch?\nB: In the canteen. The food is good and affordable.\nA: How much does a lunch cost?\nB: About four euros. The company pays the rest.",funFact:"German office canteens are legendary: subsidized hot meals, salad bars, and the social epicenter of every workplace. Currywurst on Fridays is a tradition in many Kantinen across the country."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Garderobe",src:"the cloakroom, the wardrobe",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From French 'garder' (to keep) + 'robe' (clothing).\nEveryone hangs their coat here before starting work.",example:"A: Wo kann ich meine Jacke aufhängen?\nB: In der Garderobe, gleich am Eingang.\nA: Gibt es einen Haken für mich?\nB: Ja, nimm einfach einen freien Platz.",exampleSrc:"A: Where can I hang my jacket?\nB: In the cloakroom, right at the entrance.\nA: Is there a hook for me?\nB: Yes, just take any free spot.",funFact:"In German offices, everyone hangs their coat in the Garderobe before starting work. Some companies have a strict 'no jackets at desks' policy. The Garderobe is the transition zone between outside world and office world."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Besprechung",src:"the meeting, the discussion",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Be- + sprechen (to speak). A meeting.\nGermans take Besprechungen seriously: agenda, start time, end time.",example:"A: Wann ist die Besprechung?\nB: Um zehn Uhr im Konferenzraum.\nA: Wie lange dauert sie?\nB: Ungefähr eine Stunde. Danach ist Mittagspause.",exampleSrc:"A: When is the meeting?\nB: At ten o'clock in the conference room.\nA: How long does it last?\nB: About one hour. After that is lunch break.",funFact:"Germans take Besprechungen seriously: there is an agenda, a start time, and usually an end time. Being late to a Besprechung is a serious faux pas. Five minutes early is the German on time."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Konferenz",src:"the conference",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'conferre' (to bring together).\nMore formal than a Besprechung. Konferenzräume are on every floor.",example:"A: Nächste Woche haben wir eine große Konferenz.\nB: Wie viele Teilnehmer kommen?\nA: Ungefähr fünfzig. Aus drei Abteilungen.\nB: Dann brauchen wir den großen Konferenzraum.",exampleSrc:"A: Next week we have a big conference.\nB: How many participants are coming?\nA: About fifty. From three departments.\nB: Then we need the large conference room.",funFact:"A Konferenz is more formal than a Besprechung. Conference rooms are Konferenzräume. The -enz ending in German (like Konferenz, Konkurrenz, Existenz) always comes from Latin and is always feminine."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} beginnt um zehn Uhr. Bitte komm nicht zu spät.",a:["Besprechung"],opts:["Besprechung","Garderobe","Konferenz","Kantine"],hint:"A meeting or structured discussion. From be- + sprechen (to speak).",sSrc:"The meeting starts at ten o'clock. Please do not be late."}
]},
{id:"deu_r14l1b",title:"Der erste Morgen (Teil 2)",icon:"🌅",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der erste Morgen (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Tagesablauf",src:"the daily routine, the daily schedule",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Tag (day) + Ablauf (sequence). Your daily routine.\nOn your first day, someone always explains the Tagesablauf.",example:"A: Wie ist der Tagesablauf hier?\nB: Wir fangen um acht an, Mittagspause um zwölf.\nA: Und wann ist Feierabend?\nB: Um siebzehn Uhr. Pünktlich.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the daily routine here?\nB: We start at eight, lunch break at twelve.\nA: And when is end of work?\nB: At five o'clock. Punctually.",funFact:"Germans love structure. The Tagesablauf is almost sacred: 8:00 start, 12:00 lunch, 17:00 Feierabend. Deviating from the Tagesablauf without good reason raises eyebrows."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zusammenarbeit",src:"the collaboration, the teamwork",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Zusammen (together) + Arbeit (work). Collaboration.\n'Gute Zusammenarbeit' is the highest workplace praise.",example:"A: Wie ist die Zusammenarbeit in deinem Team?\nB: Sehr gut. Wir besprechen alles gemeinsam.\nA: Das klingt ideal.\nB: Ja, gute Zusammenarbeit ist hier sehr wichtig.",exampleSrc:"A: How is the collaboration in your team?\nB: Very good. We discuss everything together.\nA: That sounds ideal.\nB: Yes, good collaboration is very important here.",funFact:"Germans value Zusammenarbeit so much they put it in job descriptions, performance reviews, and company values. 'Gute Zusammenarbeit' is the highest workplace praise you can receive."},
{type:"teach",trg:"begrüßen",src:"to welcome, to greet",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + grüßen (to greet). More thorough than casual grüßen.\n'Ich begrüße Sie herzlich' starts formal meetings.",example:"A: Guten Morgen! Ich begrüße Sie herzlich im Team.\nB: Vielen Dank! Ich freue mich sehr.\nA: Wir begrüßen jeden neuen Kollegen persönlich.\nB: Das finde ich sehr nett.",exampleSrc:"A: Good morning! I warmly welcome you to the team.\nB: Thank you very much! I am very happy.\nA: We welcome every new colleague personally.\nB: I think that is very nice.",funFact:"The be- prefix makes begrüßen more thorough than casual grüßen. 'Ich begrüße Sie herzlich' is how department heads start meetings. It signals official, warm recognition."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einrichten",src:"to set up, to furnish",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ein- (in) + richten (to arrange). To set up or furnish.\n'Seinen Arbeitsplatz einrichten' = setting up your workspace.",example:"A: Hast du deinen Arbeitsplatz schon eingerichtet?\nB: Noch nicht. Ich brauche noch einen Monitor.\nA: Der wird heute Nachmittag geliefert.\nB: Super, dann richte ich alles morgen ein.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you set up your workspace yet?\nB: Not yet. I still need a monitor.\nA: It will be delivered this afternoon.\nB: Great, then I will set everything up tomorrow.",funFact:"Einrichten means to set up or furnish. Germans take both very seriously: setting up a workspace AND furnishing an apartment. 'Sich häuslich einrichten' means to make yourself comfortable, to settle in."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Gute Zusammenarbeit ist hier sehr wichtig.' Was bedeutet Zusammenarbeit?",opts:["overtime","collaboration","daily routine","meeting"],ans:"collaboration",hint:"Zusammen (together) + Arbeit (work). Working jointly with your team."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ordnen",src:"to organize, to sort",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Dateien ordnen' = organize files.\nRelated to 'Ordnung' (order). 'Ordnung muss sein!'",example:"A: Kannst du bitte die Unterlagen ordnen?\nB: Natürlich. Nach Datum oder nach Name?\nA: Nach Datum, bitte. Die neuesten zuerst.\nB: Ist erledigt. Alles ist jetzt geordnet.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you please organize the documents?\nB: Of course. By date or by name?\nA: By date, please. The newest first.\nB: Done. Everything is organized now.",funFact:"Related to 'Ordnung' (order). The saying 'Ordnung muss sein' (there must be order) is practically the German national motto. Filing, sorting, and labeling bring Germans genuine satisfaction."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gemeinsam",src:"together, jointly, shared",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Stronger than 'zusammen.' Implies unity of purpose.\n'Gemeinsam sind wir stark' (together we are strong).",example:"A: Machen wir das Projekt gemeinsam?\nB: Ja, gemeinsam geht es schneller.\nA: Gut, dann teilen wir die Aufgaben auf.\nB: Einverstanden. Gemeinsame Arbeit ist besser.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we do the project together?\nB: Yes, together it goes faster.\nA: Good, then we divide up the tasks.\nB: Agreed. Joint work is better.",funFact:"Gemeinsam is stronger than zusammen because it implies unity of purpose, not just physical togetherness. 'Gemeinsam einsam' (together alone) is a famous German phrase for being lonely in a crowd."},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufmerksam",src:"attentive, observant",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Auf- (up) + merksam (noticing). Attentive.\n'Aufmerksam zuhören' = to listen attentively.",example:"A: Bitte sei aufmerksam in der Besprechung.\nB: Natürlich. Ich höre immer aufmerksam zu.\nA: Gut, denn es geht um wichtige Änderungen.\nB: Ich mache mir Notizen.",exampleSrc:"A: Please be attentive in the meeting.\nB: Of course. I always listen attentively.\nA: Good, because it is about important changes.\nB: I will take notes.",funFact:"'Aufmerksam zuhören' (to listen attentively) is what your new boss hopes you will do on day one. 'Eine Aufmerksamkeit' (a small attention) also means a small gift or gesture of kindness."},
{type:"mc",q:"Bitte sei aufmerksam in der Besprechung! Was bedeutet aufmerksam?",opts:["tired (nein)","attentive","quiet","late"],ans:"attentive",hint:"Auf- (up) + merksam (noticing). Listen carefully and pay attention."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ordentlich",src:"tidy, proper, decent",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Ordnung.' A tidy desk, a proper report.\n'Ordentlich arbeiten' = to work properly.",example:"A: Dein Schreibtisch ist sehr ordentlich!\nB: Danke, Ordnung muss sein.\nA: Bei mir sieht es nicht so ordentlich aus.\nB: Das kommt mit der Zeit.",exampleSrc:"A: Your desk is very tidy!\nB: Thanks, there must be order.\nA: Mine does not look so tidy.\nB: That comes with time.",funFact:"Ordentlich comes from Ordnung (order). An 'ordentlicher Professor' is a full professor (not just a tidy one). In everyday German, 'ordentlich' can also mean 'quite a lot': 'Das war ordentlich teuer!'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"fest",src:"firm, fixed, solid",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Opposite of 'locker' (loose). 'Ein fester Termin' = a fixed appointment.\n'Fest angestellt' = permanently employed.",example:"A: Hast du einen festen Vertrag?\nB: Ja, seit letztem Monat. Unbefristet.\nA: Glückwunsch! Ein fester Arbeitsplatz ist toll.\nB: Danke, ich bin sehr froh darüber.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a permanent contract?\nB: Yes, since last month. Unlimited.\nA: Congratulations! A permanent job is great.\nB: Thanks, I am very happy about it.",funFact:"Fest has many uses: ein Fest (a celebration), fest angestellt (permanently employed), festhalten (to hold on tight), feststehen (to be certain). The concept of firmness and reliability runs deep in German culture."},
{type:"teach",trg:"innen",src:"inside, indoors",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Opposite of 'außen' (outside).\n'Von innen' = from the inside. 'Nach innen' = inward.",example:"A: Ist es warm hier innen?\nB: Ja, die Heizung funktioniert gut.\nA: Von innen sieht das Büro sehr modern aus.\nB: Ja, es wurde letztes Jahr renoviert.",exampleSrc:"A: Is it warm in here?\nB: Yes, the heating works well.\nA: From inside, the office looks very modern.\nB: Yes, it was renovated last year.",funFact:"Innen and außen are the German inside/outside pair. 'Innenstadt' (inner city) is the city center. 'Innenminister' (interior minister) handles domestic affairs. 'Innere Ruhe' (inner peace) is what every German seeks."},
{type:"teach",trg:"miteinander",src:"with each other, together",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Mit (with) + einander (each other).\n'Miteinander reden' = to talk with each other.",example:"A: Wie arbeitet ihr miteinander?\nB: Sehr gut. Wir reden viel miteinander.\nA: Das ist wichtig für die Zusammenarbeit.\nB: Ja, ohne Kommunikation geht es nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you work with each other?\nB: Very well. We talk a lot with each other.\nA: That is important for collaboration.\nB: Yes, without communication it does not work.",funFact:"German has many einander-compounds: miteinander (with each other), füreinander (for each other), nebeneinander (next to each other), nacheinander (one after another). Each one is its own word."},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"helpful",art:"de-ber-office-floor",trg:"Hier ist unsere Etage. Der Flur führt zur Kantine, und am Ende vom Gang ist der Konferenzraum. Die Besprechung beginnt um zehn.",src:"Here is our floor. The hallway leads to the canteen, and at the end of the corridor is the conference room. The meeting starts at ten."},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia sagt, die Besprechung ist im Konferenzraum. Was ist ein Konferenzraum?",opts:["Der Flur","Die Garderobe","Die Kantine","Ein Besprechungsraum"],ans:"Ein Besprechungsraum",hint:"This compound word describes a dedicated space in an office where formal gatherings take place."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} beginnt um zehn Uhr im Konferenzraum.",a:["Besprechung"],opts:["Besprechung","Kantine","Garderobe","Etage"],hint:"Which word means a meeting or formal discussion?",sSrc:"The meeting starts at ten o'clock in the conference room."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Tagesablauf'?",opts:["the company, the operation","the canteen, the cafeteria","with each other, together","the daily routine, the daily schedule"],ans:"the daily routine, the daily schedule",hint:"A compound: Tag (day) + es + Ab + Lauf (course/run). How a day runs its course."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie ist {1} in deinem Team?",a:["die Zusammenarbeit"],opts:["die Zusammenarbeit","die Konferenz","der Betrieb","die Abteilung"],hint:"Zusammen (together) + Arbeit (work). The noun for working as a team.",sSrc:"How is the collaboration in your team?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'einrichten'?",opts:["to set up, to furnish","the corridor, the aisle","the hallway, the corridor","firm, fixed, solid"],ans:"to set up, to furnish",hint:"Ein- (in) + richten (to arrange/direct). To arrange the inside of a space."},
{type:"fb",s:"Kannst du bitte die Unterlagen {1}?",a:["ordnen"],opts:["ordnen","innen","begrüßen","aufmerksam"],hint:"From Ordnung (order). A verb meaning to sort or arrange systematically.",sSrc:"Can you please organize the documents?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'gemeinsam'?",opts:["the company, the operation","together, jointly, shared","the collaboration, the teamwork","the conference"],ans:"together, jointly, shared",hint:"From Gemein- (communal/mutual) + -sam. Doing something as a group, not alone."},
{type:"fb",s:"Dein Schreibtisch ist sehr {1}!",a:["ordentlich"],opts:["die Besprechung","die Kantine","der Betrieb","ordentlich"],hint:"From Ordnung (order) + -lich. An adjective for someone who keeps things neat.",sSrc:"Your desk is very tidy!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'miteinander'?",opts:["with each other, together","the company, the operation","attentive, observant","together, jointly, shared"],ans:"with each other, together",hint:"Mit (with) + ein + ander. Three parts fused into one word."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 2: Das Büro ───
{id:"deu_r14l2",title:"Das Büro",icon:"🖥️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Das Büro",desc:"Verumius sets up his workstation. Monitor, keyboard, copier. Learn the German names for everything in an office.",goals:["Learn 20 words for office equipment","Understand compound word patterns for office items","Master technical vocabulary for the German workplace"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"self-conscious",art:"de-ber-office-desk",trg:"Verumius sitzt an seinem neuen Schreibtisch. Ein Monitor, eine Tastatur, ein Kabelsalat. Sein Anzug fühlt sich immer overdressed an, wenn alle anderen Sneakers tragen.",src:"Verumius sits at his new desk. A monitor, a keyboard, a cable mess. His suit feels increasingly overdressed when everyone else is wearing sneakers."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bildschirm",src:"the screen, the monitor",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Bild (picture) + Schirm (screen/umbrella). Literally 'picture-screen.'\nUsed for any display: computer, TV, phone.",example:"A: Mein Bildschirm ist zu klein.\nB: Wir können einen größeren bestellen.\nA: Das wäre toll. Ich brauche zwei Bildschirme.\nB: Kein Problem, frag den IT-Leiter.",exampleSrc:"A: My screen is too small.\nB: We can order a bigger one.\nA: That would be great. I need two screens.\nB: No problem, ask the IT manager.",funFact:"Bild (picture) + Schirm (screen/umbrella) creates 'picture-screen.' Germans use this for any display. Das Bild is neuter but der Schirm wins the gender battle, making it masculine."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Monitor",src:"the monitor",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'monere' (to warn/watch).\nInterchangeable with Bildschirm in tech contexts.",example:"A: Ist das ein neuer Monitor?\nB: Ja, er wurde letzte Woche geliefert.\nA: Er ist sehr groß.\nB: Siebenundzwanzig Zoll. Perfekt für die Arbeit.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that a new monitor?\nB: Yes, it was delivered last week.\nA: It is very big.\nB: Twenty-seven inches. Perfect for work.",funFact:"Monitor sounds more international, Bildschirm more traditionally German. Both are used daily. In everyday conversation, many Germans now also say 'Screen' with German pronunciation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Rechner",src:"the computer, the calculator",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'rechnen' (to calculate). A computer is literally a 'calculator.'\nTaschenrechner = pocket calculator.",example:"A: Mein Rechner ist sehr langsam heute.\nB: Hast du ihn schon neu gestartet?\nA: Nein, das probiere ich mal.\nB: Das löst meistens das Problem.",exampleSrc:"A: My computer is very slow today.\nB: Have you restarted it yet?\nA: No, I will try that.\nB: That usually solves the problem.",funFact:"Before English 'Computer' took over, Rechner was the standard word. A Taschenrechner (pocket calculator) keeps the old meaning alive. Germany even had 'Großrechner' (mainframes), literally 'big calculators.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Tastatur",src:"the keyboard",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'Taste' (key/button). German keyboards have QWERTZ layout.\nY and Z are swapped. Also has keys for ä, ö, ü, ß.",example:"A: Wo ist das ß auf der Tastatur?\nB: Rechts neben der Null.\nA: Und die Umlaute?\nB: Rechts neben dem P und dem L.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the ß on the keyboard?\nB: To the right of the zero.\nA: And the umlauts?\nB: To the right of the P and the L.",funFact:"German keyboards have QWERTZ layout, not QWERTY. The Y and Z are swapped. Also, there are dedicated keys for ä, ö, ü, and ß. Switching between keyboard layouts is a daily struggle for multilingual workers."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Taste",src:"the key, the button",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From French 'taster' (to touch/feel).\nEvery button on keyboard, remote, or elevator is a Taste.",example:"A: Welche Taste muss ich drücken?\nB: Die große Taste unten. Das ist die Leertaste.\nA: Und diese kleine Taste hier?\nB: Das ist die Escape-Taste.",exampleSrc:"A: Which key do I have to press?\nB: The big key at the bottom. That is the space bar.\nA: And this little key here?\nB: That is the escape key.",funFact:"Leertaste (space bar) literally means 'empty key.' Löschtaste (delete key) means 'erase key.' German names for keyboard keys always describe what the key does."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das ß ist rechts neben der Null auf der {1}.",a:["Tastatur"],opts:["Tastatur","Festplatte","Bildschirm","Taste"],hint:"The input device you type on. German ones have QWERTZ layout.",sSrc:"The sharp s is to the right of the zero on the keyboard."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Festplatte",src:"the hard drive",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Fest (solid/fixed) + Platte (plate/disk). Literally 'fixed disk.'\n'Die Festplatte ist voll' is every office worker's nightmare.",example:"A: Meine Festplatte ist fast voll.\nB: Lösch doch alte Dateien.\nA: Oder ich brauche eine neue Festplatte.\nB: Frag die IT-Abteilung.",exampleSrc:"A: My hard drive is almost full.\nB: Delete some old files then.\nA: Or I need a new hard drive.\nB: Ask the IT department.",funFact:"'Die Festplatte ist voll' is the IT nightmare sentence every office worker dreads. Festplatte is being replaced by SSD (Solid State Drive), but Germans still call any internal storage 'Festplatte' out of habit."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Kabel",src:"the cable, the cord",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Latin 'capulum' (rope). Any cable or cord.\n'Kabelsalat' (cable salad) = tangled cables under your desk.",example:"A: Wo ist das Kabel für den Monitor?\nB: Unter dem Schreibtisch. Im Kabelsalat.\nA: Da sind so viele Kabel!\nB: Ja, das ist normaler Büro-Kabelsalat.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the cable for the monitor?\nB: Under the desk. In the cable mess.\nA: There are so many cables!\nB: Yes, that is normal office cable spaghetti.",funFact:"'Kabelsalat' (cable salad) is the beautiful German word for tangled cables under your desk. Every office has Kabelsalat. Some companies hire professionals to tame the Kabelsalat."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Steckdose",src:"the power outlet, the socket",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Stecken (to plug in) + Dose (socket/tin). A power outlet.\nGerman outlets are round (Schuko type).",example:"A: Gibt es hier eine Steckdose?\nB: Ja, unter dem Tisch.\nA: Ich brauche eine für meinen Laptop.\nB: Da drüben ist auch eine freie Steckdose.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a power outlet here?\nB: Yes, under the table.\nA: I need one for my laptop.\nB: Over there is also a free outlet.",funFact:"German outlets are round (Schuko type). Visitors from the UK or US always need an adapter. The Schuko system was invented in 1926 by Albert Büttner and is now standard in most of Europe."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Stecker",src:"the plug",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'stecken' (to plug). Der Stecker goes into die Steckdose.\nSimple, logical compound naming.",example:"A: Der Stecker passt nicht in die Steckdose.\nB: Das ist ein britischer Stecker. Du brauchst einen Adapter.\nA: Wo bekomme ich einen?\nB: Frag den Hausmeister.",exampleSrc:"A: The plug does not fit in the outlet.\nB: That is a British plug. You need an adapter.\nA: Where do I get one?\nB: Ask the caretaker.",funFact:"Der Stecker goes into die Steckdose. Stecker, Steckdose, stecken: all from the same root. German makes hardware vocabulary self-explanatory through compound words."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kopierer",src:"the copier, the copy machine",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'kopieren' (to copy) + -er (machine suffix).\n'Der Kopierer ist kaputt' is the most common office complaint.",example:"A: Wo steht der Kopierer?\nB: Im Flur, neben der Kaffeküche.\nA: Funktioniert er?\nB: Meistens. Aber er ist oft kaputt.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the copier?\nB: In the hallway, next to the coffee kitchen.\nA: Does it work?\nB: Usually. But it is often broken.",funFact:"'Der Kopierer ist kaputt' (the copier is broken) might be the most common office complaint in Germany. Every new employee has to learn the copier's quirks. Each office copier has its own personality."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kopie",src:"the copy",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'copia' (abundance). 'Eine Kopie machen' = to make a copy.\nGerman bureaucracy runs on Kopien of everything.",example:"A: Ich brauche drei Kopien von diesem Dokument.\nB: Kein Problem. Farbe oder schwarz-weiß?\nA: Schwarz-weiß reicht.\nB: Hier sind die Kopien.",exampleSrc:"A: I need three copies of this document.\nB: No problem. Color or black-and-white?\nA: Black-and-white is enough.\nB: Here are the copies.",funFact:"The bureaucratic soul of Germany runs on Kopien of everything. Insurance claims need Kopien, tax returns need Kopien, apartment applications need Kopien. A good German always has Kopien ready."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Der Stecker passt nicht in die Steckdose.' Was ist eine Steckdose?",opts:["a plug","a power outlet","a cable","a hard drive"],ans:"a power outlet",hint:"Where you plug in electrical devices. Stecken (to plug) + Dose (socket)."}
]},
{id:"deu_r14l2b",title:"Das Büro (Teil 2)",icon:"🖥️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Das Büro (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Ordner",src:"the binder, the folder",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'ordnen' (to organize). Both physical ring binders AND computer folders.\nGermans keep Ordner for everything.",example:"A: In welchem Ordner ist der Vertrag?\nB: Im blauen Ordner auf dem Regal.\nA: Und die digitale Version?\nB: Im Ordner 'Verträge' auf dem Server.",exampleSrc:"A: In which folder is the contract?\nB: In the blue binder on the shelf.\nA: And the digital version?\nB: In the 'Contracts' folder on the server.",funFact:"Germans keep physical Ordner for everything: taxes, insurance, contracts, warranties. The Ordner culture is legendary. IKEA's bestselling storage item in Germany is the Billy bookcase to hold Ordner."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Regal",src:"the shelf, the bookcase",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Latin 'regalis' (royal).\nBücherregal (bookshelf), Aktenregal (file shelf).",example:"A: Wo stelle ich die Ordner hin?\nB: Ins Regal, dritte Reihe von oben.\nA: Das Regal ist schon ziemlich voll.\nB: Dann bestellen wir ein neues.",exampleSrc:"A: Where do I put the binders?\nB: On the shelf, third row from the top.\nA: The shelf is already quite full.\nB: Then we will order a new one.",funFact:"IKEA's Billy Regal is Germany's favorite bookcase. Every German household owns at least one. Bücherregal (bookshelf) and Aktenregal (file shelf) are in every German office."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mappe",src:"the folder, the portfolio",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Thinner than an Ordner. For meetings and presentations.\nAktenmappe = document folder. Schulmappe = school bag.",example:"A: Hast du die Unterlagen in der Mappe?\nB: Ja, alles ist drin. Berichte, Listen, Kopien.\nA: Perfekt, wir brauchen die Mappe für die Besprechung.\nB: Ich bringe sie gleich mit.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have the documents in the folder?\nB: Yes, everything is in there. Reports, lists, copies.\nA: Perfect, we need the folder for the meeting.\nB: I will bring it right away.",funFact:"A Mappe is thinner than an Ordner. Students carry a Schulmappe, professionals carry a Mappe to meetings. An Aktenmappe holds important documents. In art, a Mappe is a portfolio."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kuli",src:"the ballpoint pen",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Short for 'Kugelschreiber' (ball-point writer).\nOne of Germany's greatest word shortcuts: 16 letters to 4.",example:"A: Hast du einen Kuli?\nB: Ja, hier. Blau oder schwarz?\nA: Schwarz, bitte.\nB: Bitte. Aber gib ihn mir zurück!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a pen?\nB: Yes, here. Blue or black?\nA: Black, please.\nB: Here you go. But give it back to me!",funFact:"Kuli is short for Kugelschreiber (ball-point writer). One of Germany's greatest word shortcuts: 16 letters to just 4. The full compound has Kugel (ball) + Schreiber (writer). Invented in 1938 by Hungarian inventor László Bíró."},
{type:"fb",s:"In welchem {1} ist der Vertrag? Im blauen auf dem Regal.",a:["Ordner"],opts:["Ordner","Kuli","Regal","Mappe"],hint:"A ring binder for filing and storing documents. Every German office shelf has rows of them.",sSrc:"In which binder is the contract? In the blue one on the shelf."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Tabelle",src:"the table, the spreadsheet",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'tabella' (small board).\nExcel-Tabellen rule German office life.",example:"A: Kannst du eine Tabelle mit den Zahlen machen?\nB: Klar, in Excel oder auf Papier?\nA: In Excel, bitte. Mit allen Abteilungen.\nB: Wird gemacht. Bis morgen?",exampleSrc:"A: Can you make a table with the numbers?\nB: Sure, in Excel or on paper?\nA: In Excel, please. With all departments.\nB: Will be done. By tomorrow?",funFact:"Excel-Tabellen rule German office life. 'Ich mache eine Tabelle' means someone is about to organize everything into neat rows and columns. Germany's love of data and order meets perfectly in the Tabelle."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ausdrucken",src:"to print out",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Aus- (out) + drucken (to print/press). Separable verb.\n'Können Sie das ausdrucken?' is heard constantly in German offices.",example:"A: Können Sie den Bericht ausdrucken?\nB: Natürlich. Wie viele Kopien?\nA: Drei, bitte. Und in Farbe.\nB: Wird sofort ausgedruckt.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you print out the report?\nB: Of course. How many copies?\nA: Three, please. And in color.\nB: Will be printed out right away.",funFact:"Despite digitalization, Germans still print a lot. 'Können Sie das ausdrucken?' is heard dozens of times a day. Germany has been slower than other countries to adopt a fully digital office. Paper feels more official."},
{type:"teach",trg:"kopieren",src:"to copy",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb from Latin/French.\n-ieren verbs always conjugate regularly, and the past participle has no ge-.",example:"A: Bitte kopieren Sie diese Unterlagen.\nB: Wie viele Kopien brauchen Sie?\nA: Fünf Stück. Doppelseitig.\nB: Wird sofort kopiert.",exampleSrc:"A: Please copy these documents.\nB: How many copies do you need?\nA: Five. Double-sided.\nB: Will be copied right away.",funFact:"The -ieren verbs are easy: they always conjugate regularly, and the past participle has no ge-. Kopiert, not gekopiert. This rule works for telefonieren, installieren, organisieren, and hundreds more."},
{type:"teach",trg:"klicken",src:"to click",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Onomatopoeia borrowed from English.\n'Klicken Sie auf den Link' (click on the link).",example:"A: Wo muss ich klicken?\nB: Auf den grünen Knopf oben rechts.\nA: Diesen hier?\nB: Genau. Einmal klicken reicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Where do I have to click?\nB: On the green button in the upper right.\nA: This one here?\nB: Exactly. One click is enough.",funFact:"German tech vocabulary freely borrows English words and adds German grammar. Klicken, downloaden, liken, chatten. The words are English, but they conjugate German: ich klicke, du klickst, er klickt."},
{type:"teach",trg:"tippen",src:"to type, to tap",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From English 'to tip/tap.' 'Tippen Sie Ihr Passwort ein.'\nAlso means to guess/bet: 'Ich tippe auf Bayern.'",example:"A: Kannst du schnell tippen?\nB: Ja, ungefähr siebzig Wörter pro Minute.\nA: Das ist beeindruckend!\nB: Übung macht den Meister.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you type fast?\nB: Yes, about seventy words per minute.\nA: That is impressive!\nB: Practice makes perfect.",funFact:"Tippen means to type AND to bet/guess. 'Ich tippe auf Bayern' means 'I bet on Bayern Munich.' Tipps (tips/advice) come from the same root. In the office, 'tippen' is always about typing."},
{type:"mc",q:"Du musst ein Dokument drucken. Welches Gerät brauchst du?",opts:["Den Kopierer","Die Tastatur","Den Ordner","Das Regal"],ans:"Den Kopierer",hint:"Which machine produces physical paper copies of documents?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Bitte {1} Sie die Datei aus.",a:["drucken"],opts:["drucken","klicken","tippen","kopieren"],hint:"Which verb means to print something on paper?",sSrc:"Please print out the file."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Bildschirm",src:"screen/monitor"},{trg:"die Tastatur",src:"keyboard"},{trg:"die Festplatte",src:"hard drive"},{trg:"die Steckdose",src:"power outlet"},{trg:"der Kuli",src:"ballpoint pen"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"conspiratorial",art:"de-ber-office-hallway",trg:"So, dein Arbeitsplatz ist eingerichtet. Jetzt zeige ich dir den wichtigsten Ort im ganzen Betrieb. Die Kaffeküche.",src:"So, your workspace is set up. Now I will show you the most important place in the whole company. The coffee kitchen."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Tabelle'?",opts:["the table, the spreadsheet","to type, to tap","the plug","the key, the button"],ans:"the table, the spreadsheet",hint:"Sounds like its English equivalent. In German, it means a data grid, not furniture."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 3: Die Kaffeküche ───
{id:"deu_r14l3",title:"Die Kaffeküche",icon:"☕",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Kaffeküche",desc:"Mia shows Verumius the office kitchen. Special rules apply here: notes on the wall, passive-aggressive signs, and the coffee is freshly made every morning.",goals:["Learn vocabulary for colleagues and job titles","Discover the unwritten rules of the Kaffeküche","Understand the passive construction: werden + Partizip II"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"direct",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche",trg:"So, das hier ist die Kaffeküche. Hier gelten besondere Regeln. Siehst du die Zettel an der Wand?",src:"So, this is the coffee kitchen. Special rules apply here. Do you see the notes on the wall?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"amused",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche-notes",trg:"An der Wand hängen bunte Zettel: 'Bitte Spülmaschine ausräumen!' 'Milch mit NAMEN beschriften!' 'Der Kaffee wird jeden Morgen frisch gemacht!'",src:"On the wall hang colorful notes: 'Please empty the dishwasher!' 'Label milk with your NAME!' 'The coffee is made fresh every morning!'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Leiter",src:"the leader, the manager (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'leiten' (to lead). Also means 'ladder' when feminine (die Leiter).\nSame word, different gender, different meaning.",example:"A: Wer ist der Leiter dieser Abteilung?\nB: Herr Schmidt. Er leitet das Team seit fünf Jahren.\nA: Ist er nett?\nB: Ja, sehr. Er begrüßt jeden persönlich.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is the manager of this department?\nB: Herr Schmidt. He has managed the team for five years.\nA: Is he nice?\nB: Yes, very. He greets everyone personally.",funFact:"Der Leiter (masculine) = leader/manager. Die Leiter (feminine) = ladder. Same word, different gender, completely different meaning. Classic German trap that even native speakers joke about."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Leiterin",src:"the leader, the manager (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Leiter + -in. German requires gendered job titles.\nCompanies often write 'Teamleiter/in' to include both.",example:"A: Frau Müller ist die Leiterin unserer Abteilung.\nB: Seit wann?\nA: Seit drei Jahren. Sie macht einen tollen Job.\nB: Das habe ich gehört.",exampleSrc:"A: Frau Müller is the manager of our department.\nB: Since when?\nA: For three years. She does a great job.\nB: I have heard that.",funFact:"Germany requires gendered job titles: der Leiter/die Leiterin. Companies increasingly write 'Teamleiter:in' with a gender colon to include everyone. The debate over gender-neutral language is ongoing in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Leitung",src:"the leadership, the management, the line",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Unter der Leitung von...' = under the leadership of.\nAlso: Telefonleitung (phone line), Wasserleitung (water pipe).",example:"A: Wer hat die Leitung des Projekts?\nB: Frau Müller. Sie leitet alles.\nA: Unter ihrer Leitung läuft es gut.\nB: Ja, sie ist eine gute Leiterin.",exampleSrc:"A: Who has the leadership of the project?\nB: Frau Müller. She manages everything.\nA: Under her leadership things run well.\nB: Yes, she is a good manager.",funFact:"Leitung means leadership, management, or line/pipe. One word, many pipes: Telefonleitung (phone line), Wasserleitung (water pipe), Gasleitung (gas line). Context is always king in German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mitarbeiterin",src:"the colleague, the employee (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Mit- (with) + Arbeiterin (worker). Female colleague.\nGermans increasingly use 'Mitarbeitende' (gender-neutral).",example:"A: Wie viele Mitarbeiterinnen gibt es in deinem Team?\nB: Sieben Mitarbeiterinnen und fünf Mitarbeiter.\nA: Und ihr arbeitet alle auf dieser Etage?\nB: Ja, wir sitzen alle zusammen.",exampleSrc:"A: How many female employees are in your team?\nB: Seven female and five male employees.\nA: And you all work on this floor?\nB: Yes, we all sit together.",funFact:"Germans increasingly use 'Mitarbeitende' (gender-neutral) in official contexts. Your Mitarbeiter and Mitarbeiterinnen are your coworkers. In job ads, you will often see 'Mitarbeiter (m/w/d)' meaning male/female/diverse."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Leitung des Projekts liegt bei Frau Müller.' Was ist Leitung?",opts:["a ladder","a phone line","a guideline","the leadership/management"],ans:"the leadership/management",hint:"From 'leiten' (to lead). Can also mean a pipe or wire, but here it refers to managing a project."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Hausmeister",src:"the caretaker, the janitor",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Haus (house) + Meister (master). The building caretaker.\nFixes everything, knows everything, has all the keys.",example:"A: Die Heizung funktioniert nicht.\nB: Ruf den Hausmeister an. Er repariert alles.\nA: Wo finde ich ihn?\nB: Im Keller. Er hat sein Büro dort.",exampleSrc:"A: The heating does not work.\nB: Call the caretaker. He repairs everything.\nA: Where do I find him?\nB: In the basement. He has his office there.",funFact:"In German offices and apartment buildings, the Hausmeister is the person who fixes everything, knows everything, and has all the keys. A good Hausmeister is treated like gold."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sekretärin",src:"the secretary, the administrative assistant (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'secretarius' (confidant).\nModern offices use 'Assistenz' or 'Office-Management.'",example:"A: Wer organisiert die Termine hier?\nB: Die Sekretärin, Frau Weber.\nA: Sitzt sie am Empfang?\nB: Ja, gleich am Eingang. Sie hilft dir bei allem.",exampleSrc:"A: Who organizes the appointments here?\nB: The secretary, Frau Weber.\nA: Does she sit at the reception?\nB: Yes, right at the entrance. She helps you with everything.",funFact:"Modern German offices increasingly use 'Assistenz' or 'Office-Management' instead of Sekretärin. But the word remains widely understood. The role has evolved from typing pools to managing entire departments."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Dienst",src:"the service, the duty",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Im Dienst' = on duty. 'Kundendienst' = customer service.\n'Dienst ist Dienst und Schnaps ist Schnaps' = work and pleasure do not mix.",example:"A: Bist du heute im Dienst?\nB: Ja, ich habe Dienst bis achtzehn Uhr.\nA: Und morgen?\nB: Morgen habe ich frei. Kein Dienst.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you on duty today?\nB: Yes, I am on duty until six PM.\nA: And tomorrow?\nB: Tomorrow I am off. No duty.",funFact:"'Dienst ist Dienst und Schnaps ist Schnaps' means work and pleasure do not mix. It is a very German saying. Dienstleistung (service provision) is the backbone of the German service economy."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Überstunde",src:"the overtime hour",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Über- (over) + Stunde (hour). Germans track Überstunden meticulously.\nWorking too many is seen negatively, not as dedication.",example:"A: Wie viele Überstunden hast du diese Woche?\nB: Nur zwei. Mehr will ich nicht.\nA: In meiner alten Firma waren es oft zehn.\nB: Das ist zu viel. Hier werden Überstunden genau gezählt.",exampleSrc:"A: How many overtime hours do you have this week?\nB: Only two. I do not want more.\nA: At my old company it was often ten.\nB: That is too much. Here overtime is counted precisely.",funFact:"Germans track Überstunden meticulously. Many contracts cap them. Working too many Überstunden is seen as poor time management, not dedication. The Betriebsrat (works council) watches overtime closely."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Terminkalender",src:"the schedule, the planner",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Termin (appointment) + Kalender (calendar). Your daily planner.\nIf it is not in the Kalender, it does not exist.",example:"A: Hast du morgen Zeit für eine Besprechung?\nB: Moment, ich schaue in meinen Terminkalender.\nA: Geht es um zehn Uhr?\nB: Ja, zehn Uhr ist frei. Ich trage es ein.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have time for a meeting tomorrow?\nB: One moment, I will check my schedule.\nA: Is ten o'clock okay?\nB: Yes, ten o'clock is free. I will write it in.",funFact:"Germans live by their Terminkalender. If it is not in the Kalender, it does not exist. Spontaneous meetings are rare. Everything gets a Termin. 'Ich habe keinen Termin frei' is the polite German no."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Leiter",src:"the manager (m)"},{trg:"die Leiterin",src:"the manager (f)"},{trg:"die Mitarbeiterin",src:"the employee (f)"},{trg:"der Hausmeister",src:"the caretaker"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Wer organisiert die Termine im Büro?",opts:["Der Hausmeister","Die Sekretärin","Der Leiter","Die Mitarbeiterin"],ans:"Die Sekretärin",hint:"This person sits at reception and helps with scheduling and administrative tasks."},
{type:"fb",s:"Herr Schmidt hat viele {1} diese Woche.",a:["Überstunden"],opts:["Überstunden","Dienste","Terminkalender","Leitungen"],hint:"Extra hours worked beyond the normal schedule. Tracked meticulously in German offices.",sSrc:"Herr Schmidt has many overtime hours this week."},
{type:"fb",s:"Frau Müller hat die {1} des Projekts.",a:["Leitung"],opts:["Leitung","Überstunde","Leiterin","Dienst"],hint:"The management or leadership of a project. Not the person, but the role.",sSrc:"Frau Müller has the leadership of the project."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Leiter",src:"the manager (male)"},{trg:"die Überstunde",src:"the overtime hour"},{trg:"der Terminkalender",src:"the schedule, the planner"},{trg:"der Dienst",src:"the service, the duty"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich habe Dienst bis achtzehn Uhr.' Was bedeutet das?",opts:["Ich gehe um 18 Uhr zum Arzt","Ich habe frei ab 18 Uhr","Ich arbeite bis 18 Uhr","Ich komme um 18 Uhr an"],ans:"Ich arbeite bis 18 Uhr",hint:"Having Dienst means being on duty, actively working at your position."}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Im Büro unterwegs ───
{id:"deu_r14l4",title:"Im Büro unterwegs",icon:"🏢",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Im Büro unterwegs",desc:"From wall decorations to carpet choices, from cleaning schedules to the passive voice: learn the vocabulary and grammar of everyday German office life.",goals:["Learn vocabulary for office objects and environments","Master the werden passive (Präsens)","Describe office routines and rules"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wand",src:"the wall (interior)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Interior wall. Not to be confused with Mauer (exterior/freestanding wall).\nDie Berliner Mauer was THE wall. Die Wand is for hanging pictures.",example:"A: Siehst du die Zettel an der Wand?\nB: Ja, da hängen viele Regeln.\nA: Jeder klebt seine eigenen Zettel an die Wand.\nB: Die Kaffeküche hat die meisten Zettel.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you see the notes on the wall?\nB: Yes, there are many rules hanging there.\nA: Everyone sticks their own notes on the wall.\nB: The coffee kitchen has the most notes.",funFact:"Die Wand (interior wall) versus die Mauer (exterior/freestanding wall). Die Berliner Mauer was THE Wall. In offices, die Wand is where passive-aggressive notes, calendars, and motivational posters live."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Teppich",src:"the carpet, the rug",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Teppichboden' = wall-to-wall carpet. Very common in German offices.\n'Unter den Teppich kehren' = to sweep under the rug.",example:"A: Warum liegt hier überall Teppich?\nB: Teppichboden ist in deutschen Büros normal.\nA: In meinem Land haben Büros Fliesen.\nB: Hier nicht. Der Teppich dämpft den Lärm.",exampleSrc:"A: Why is there carpet everywhere here?\nB: Wall-to-wall carpet is normal in German offices.\nA: In my country offices have tiles.\nB: Not here. The carpet dampens the noise.",funFact:"Teppichboden (wall-to-wall carpet) is standard in German offices. 'Unter den Teppich kehren' (to sweep under the rug) means to hide a problem. 'Jemanden auf dem Teppich halten' means to keep someone grounded."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Spiegel",src:"the mirror",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Also the name of Germany's most famous news magazine.\n'Spiegelbild' (mirror image) = reflection.",example:"A: Gibt es einen Spiegel im Büro?\nB: Ja, in der Garderobe hängt einer.\nA: Gut, ich will schauen, ob mein Anzug gut sitzt.\nB: Du siehst gut aus, keine Sorge.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a mirror in the office?\nB: Yes, there is one in the cloakroom.\nA: Good, I want to check if my suit fits well.\nB: You look good, no worries.",funFact:"Der Spiegel is also the name of Germany's most famous news magazine, founded in 1947. 'Spiegel' literally means mirror, reflecting the magazine's mission to hold a mirror to society."},
{type:"fb",s:"Siehst du die Zettel an der {1}? Hier gelten besondere Regeln.",a:["Wand"],opts:["Wand","Decke","Teppich","Spiegel"],hint:"The interior surface where notes and calendars are posted. Not the ceiling.",sSrc:"Do you see the notes on the wall? Special rules apply here."},
{type:"teach",trg:"leiten",src:"to lead, to manage",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Eine Abteilung leiten' = to manage a department.\nAlso: to conduct (electricity, water).",example:"A: Wer leitet die Besprechung heute?\nB: Frau Müller. Sie leitet immer die Montagsbesprechung.\nA: Leitet sie auch das Projekt?\nB: Ja, das ganze Projekt wird von ihr geleitet.",exampleSrc:"A: Who leads the meeting today?\nB: Frau Müller. She always leads the Monday meeting.\nA: Does she also lead the project?\nB: Yes, the entire project is led by her.",funFact:"Leiten means to lead, manage, or conduct. A Leiter leitet. Electricity is geleitet through Leitungen (lines). Water is geleitet through Wasserleitungen. Everything in German gets leitet somewhere."},
{type:"teach",trg:"reinigen",src:"to clean",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"More formal than 'putzen.' 'Chemisch reinigen' = dry cleaning.\nReinigungsplan (cleaning schedule) is on every office kitchen wall.",example:"A: Wer reinigt die Kaffeküche?\nB: Wir alle. Es gibt einen Reinigungsplan.\nA: An welchem Tag bin ich dran?\nB: Am Mittwoch. Dann wird die Küche von dir gereinigt.",exampleSrc:"A: Who cleans the coffee kitchen?\nB: All of us. There is a cleaning schedule.\nA: Which day is my turn?\nB: Wednesday. Then the kitchen is cleaned by you.",funFact:"Office kitchens always have a Reinigungsplan (cleaning schedule) on the wall. Germans take collective cleanliness seriously. 'Chemisch reinigen' means dry cleaning. A Reinigung is a dry cleaner's shop."},
{type:"teach",trg:"erledigen",src:"to complete, to take care of",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Das ist erledigt' = that is done. One of the most satisfying German sentences.\nMeans you finished a task completely.",example:"A: Hast du die Aufgabe erledigt?\nB: Ja, alles erledigt. Fertig.\nA: Perfekt. Dann können wir weitermachen.\nB: Was muss als Nächstes erledigt werden?",exampleSrc:"A: Have you completed the task?\nB: Yes, all done. Finished.\nA: Perfect. Then we can continue.\nB: What needs to be completed next?",funFact:"'Das ist erledigt!' (That is done!) is one of the most satisfying German sentences. In office culture, erledigen means you finished a task completely. No loose ends, no follow-up needed."},
{type:"teach",trg:"besprechen",src:"to discuss",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + sprechen (to speak). More structured than 'reden' (to talk).\n'Wir müssen das besprechen' = we need to discuss this.",example:"A: Können wir das Projekt heute besprechen?\nB: Ja, um vierzehn Uhr. In der Besprechung.\nA: Gut. Ich bereite die Unterlagen vor.\nB: Perfekt. Das müssen wir gründlich besprechen.",exampleSrc:"A: Can we discuss the project today?\nB: Yes, at two o'clock. In the meeting.\nA: Good. I will prepare the documents.\nB: Perfect. We need to discuss this thoroughly.",funFact:"Besprechen is more structured than reden (to talk). 'Wir müssen das besprechen' is the calm German way of saying 'we need to talk.' A Besprechung is a besprechen-event."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das ist erledigt!' Was bedeutet erledigen?",opts:["to discuss thoroughly","to clean up completely","to complete/take care of","to organize and schedule"],ans:"to complete/take care of",hint:"One of the most satisfying German sentences. It means a task is fully finished with no loose ends."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anstrengend",src:"exhausting, strenuous, tiring",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'anstrengen' (to exert). 'Ein anstrengender Tag.'\n'Das war anstrengend!' after a long meeting.",example:"A: Wie war dein erster Tag?\nB: Anstrengend! So viele neue Namen und Regeln.\nA: Der erste Tag ist immer anstrengend.\nB: Morgen wird es bestimmt besser.",exampleSrc:"A: How was your first day?\nB: Exhausting! So many new names and rules.\nA: The first day is always exhausting.\nB: Tomorrow it will certainly be better.",funFact:"'Anstrengend' is the go-to German word for anything tiring. A long meeting? Anstrengend. A difficult colleague? Anstrengend. Monday morning? Anstrengend. It covers physical and mental exhaustion equally."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einheitlich",src:"uniform, consistent, standardized",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Einheit' (unity). 'Einheitliche Regeln' = uniform rules.\nGermans love einheitliche Systeme.",example:"A: Gibt es einheitliche Regeln für alle Abteilungen?\nB: Ja, die Regeln gelten einheitlich im ganzen Betrieb.\nA: Das ist gut. So weiß jeder, was gilt.\nB: Genau. Einheitlichkeit ist hier wichtig.",exampleSrc:"A: Are there uniform rules for all departments?\nB: Yes, the rules apply uniformly throughout the whole company.\nA: That is good. So everyone knows what applies.\nB: Exactly. Uniformity is important here.",funFact:"Germans love einheitliche systems. The DIN (Deutsches Institut für Normung) creates standardized norms for everything from paper sizes (DIN A4) to beer glass shapes. Einheitlichkeit runs deep in German culture."},
{type:"teach",trg:"technisch",src:"technical",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Technik' (technology/technique).\n'Technische Probleme' are every IT department's daily bread.",example:"A: Wir haben ein technisches Problem mit dem Rechner.\nB: Welche Art von technischem Problem?\nA: Der Bildschirm bleibt schwarz.\nB: Das klingt nach einem Kabel-Problem.",exampleSrc:"A: We have a technical problem with the computer.\nB: What kind of technical problem?\nA: The screen stays black.\nB: That sounds like a cable problem.",funFact:"'Technisch gesehen' (technically speaking) is a common German phrase used to be precise. Germans value technical precision in language as much as in engineering."},
{type:"teach",trg:"digital",src:"digital",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Same as English. 'Digitale Transformation' is the big topic.\n'Digitaler Wandel' (digital change) is reshaping German offices.",example:"A: Ist euer Büro schon komplett digital?\nB: Fast. Wir haben noch viele Ordner aus Papier.\nA: Die digitale Transformation braucht Zeit.\nB: Ja, aber wir arbeiten daran.",exampleSrc:"A: Is your office already completely digital?\nB: Almost. We still have many paper binders.\nA: Digital transformation takes time.\nB: Yes, but we are working on it.",funFact:"Germany's 'Digitalisierung' (digitalization) has been slower than in many countries. The famous German Fax machine still exists in many offices. 'Digital first' is the goal, but paper still rules in many Betriebe."},
{type:"teach",trg:"aktualisieren",src:"to update",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From 'aktuell' (current) + -isieren. Not separable.\n'Die Software aktualisieren' = to update the software.",example:"A: Hast du den Terminkalender aktualisiert?\nB: Ja, ich habe ihn gerade aktualisiert.\nA: Gut. Er muss immer aktuell sein.\nB: Ich aktualisiere ihn jeden Montag.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you update the schedule?\nB: Yes, I just updated it.\nA: Good. It always needs to be up to date.\nB: I update it every Monday.",funFact:"The -isieren ending makes Latin/Greek roots into regular German verbs. Aktuell (current) becomes aktualisieren (to make current). Same pattern: digital/digitalisieren, optimal/optimieren."},
{type:"verb_table",title:"werden: Vollständige Konjugation (Präsens)",groups:[{label:"Singular",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"werde",src:"I become"},{pronoun:"du",form:"wirst",src:"you become"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"wird",src:"he/she/it becomes"}]},{label:"Plural",rows:[{pronoun:"wir",form:"werden",src:"we become"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"werdet",src:"you all become"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"werden",src:"they/you (formal) become"}]}],note:"Werden is irregular: e to i in du/er. Note the vowel changes: werde, wirst, wird.",deepDive:{title:"Werden: Three Roles",text:"Werden has three different functions:\n\n1. Full verb 'werden' (to become):\nEr wird Arzt. (He is becoming a doctor.)\n\n2. Passive auxiliary:\nDer Kaffee wird gemacht. (Coffee is being made.)\n\n3. Future auxiliary:\nIch werde kommen. (I will come.)\n\nSame form, three meanings. Context decides."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"werden: Präteritum (wurde)",groups:[{label:"Singular",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"wurde",src:"I became"},{pronoun:"du",form:"wurdest",src:"you became"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"wurde",src:"he/she/it became"}]},{label:"Plural",rows:[{pronoun:"wir",form:"wurden",src:"we became"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"wurdet",src:"you all became"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"wurden",src:"they/you (formal) became"}]}],note:"Wurde is the Präteritum of werden. Used for passive Präteritum: 'Es wurde gebaut.' Very common in news and written German.",deepDive:{title:"Spoken vs. Written Passive",text:"In spoken German, Perfekt passive is sometimes preferred:\n'Es ist gemacht worden.'\n\nBut Präteritum passive dominates in news and texts:\n'Es wurde bekannt gegeben, dass...'"}},
{type:"tip",title:"Passiv Präsens: werden + Partizip II",text:"In English: 'Coffee is made.' In German: 'Kaffee wird gemacht.'\n\nThe passive is formed with a conjugated form of werden plus a Partizip II at the end of the clause.\n\nWerden is the helper verb for ALL passive sentences:\n- ich werde\n- du wirst\n- er/sie/es wird\n- wir werden\n- sie/Sie werden\n\nThe person doing the action often disappears:\n'Der Kaffee wird gemacht.' By whom? Nobody knows.\n\nThe passive loves hiding responsibility.\nOffice signs love the passive because rules apply to everyone.",deepDive:{title:"Why Passive in the Office?",text:"German offices use the passive voice constantly:\n'Hier wird nicht geraucht.' (Smoking is not done here.)\n'Die Tür wird um 18 Uhr geschlossen.' (The door is closed at 6.)\n\nThe passive removes the 'who' and focuses on the 'what.'\nIt makes rules feel universal, not personal.\n'Du sollst nicht rauchen' (you should not smoke) feels like an order.\n'Hier wird nicht geraucht' feels like a law of nature.\n\nThis is why every Kaffeküche note uses passive voice."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Passiv Präsens: werden + Partizip II",groups:[{label:"Singular",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"werde gemacht",src:"I am being made"},{pronoun:"du",form:"wirst gemacht",src:"you are being made"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"wird gemacht",src:"he/she/it is being made"}]},{label:"Plural",rows:[{pronoun:"wir",form:"werden gemacht",src:"we are being made"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"werdet gemacht",src:"you (pl.) are being made"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"werden gemacht",src:"they/you (formal) are being made"}]}],note:"The past participle always goes to the END of the clause."},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"matter-of-fact",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche",trg:"Der Kaffee wird jeden Morgen um acht gemacht. Die Spülmaschine wird nach dem Mittagessen ausgeräumt. Das sind die Regeln.",src:"The coffee is made every morning at eight. The dishwasher is emptied after lunch. Those are the rules."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Der Kaffee wird um 8 gemacht.' Was bedeutet dieser Satz?",opts:["Jemand hat den Kaffee gestern Morgen um 8 Uhr gemacht","Es gibt hier leider keinen Kaffee um 8 Uhr","Der Kaffee wird erst morgen früh um 8 Uhr gemacht","Der Kaffee wird jeden Morgen um 8 Uhr zubereitet"],ans:"Der Kaffee wird jeden Morgen um 8 Uhr zubereitet",hint:"The sentence describes a habitual action happening at a fixed time each morning, not a past or future event."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Spülmaschine {1} nach dem Essen ausgeräumt.",a:["wird"],opts:["wird","werden","wurde","wirst"],hint:"The dishwasher (singular, she/it) IS emptied. Third person singular of werden.",sSrc:"The dishwasher is emptied after the meal."},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia sagt: 'Frau Schneider leitet unsere Abteilung.' Was ist Frau Schneiders Rolle?",opts:["Sie ist die Hausmeisterin","Sie ist die Abteilungsleiterin","Sie ist eine neue Mitarbeiterin","Sie ist die Sekretärin"],ans:"Sie ist die Abteilungsleiterin",hint:"Leiten means to lead or manage. Someone who leitet is a Leiter/in."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Der Terminkalender {1} jeden Montag {2}.",blanks:{"1":"wird","2":"aktualisiert"},pool:["wird","wurde","aktualisiert","gemacht","werden"],hint:"The schedule IS (present) updated. Werden in third person singular + past participle at end.",sSrc:"The schedule is updated every Monday."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"overwhelmed",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche",trg:"Zettel an der Wand. Regeln für den Kaffee. Regeln für die Spülmaschine. Regeln für die Milch. Gibt es auch Regeln für das Atmen?",src:"Notes on the wall. Rules for the coffee. Rules for the dishwasher. Rules for the milk. Are there also rules for breathing?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie war dein erster Arbeitstag? So viele neue Namen und Regeln!",opts:["Einheitlich!","Technisch!","Anstrengend!","Digital!"],ans:"Anstrengend!",hint:"This adjective describes something that leaves you tired and drained."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Regeln gelten {1} im ganzen Betrieb.",a:"einheitlich",opts:["einheitlich","anstrengend","technisch","digital"],hint:"An adjective meaning uniform, consistent, the same for everyone.",sSrc:"The rules apply uniformly throughout the whole company."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ist euer Büro schon komplett ___? Fast, wir haben noch viele Ordner aus Papier.",opts:["technisch","einheitlich","aktuell","digital"],ans:"digital",hint:"The opposite of paper-based. Think screens, software, and the modern office."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 4: Grammatik im Büro ───
{id:"deu_r14l5",title:"Grammatik im Büro",icon:"📝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Grammatik im Büro",desc:"Passive Präteritum, relative clauses, and how to talk about the past in a German office. Three grammar structures you will need every day.",goals:["Master the passive Präteritum: wurde + Partizip II","Learn relative clauses with der/die/das (nominative, accusative, dative)","Combine both structures in office situations"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"warning",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche",trg:"Eine Sache noch. Nimm niemals den letzten Kaffee, ohne neuen zu kochen. Das ist die goldene Regel der Kaffeküche.",src:"One more thing. Never take the last coffee without making a fresh pot. That is the golden rule of the coffee kitchen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Auftrag",src:"the order, the task, the assignment",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Im Auftrag von' (on behalf of) appears on every official letter.\nFrom 'auftragen' (to assign). Your boss gives you Aufträge.",example:"A: Hast du den Auftrag von Frau Müller bekommen?\nB: Ja, ich soll den Bericht bis Freitag schreiben.\nA: Das ist ein wichtiger Auftrag.\nB: Ich weiß. Er wird rechtzeitig erledigt.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you get the assignment from Frau Müller?\nB: Yes, I am supposed to write the report by Friday.\nA: That is an important assignment.\nB: I know. It will be completed on time.",funFact:"'Im Auftrag von' (on behalf of) appears on every official German letter. In business emails, 'i.A.' (im Auftrag) before your name means you are signing on someone else's behalf."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Direktor",src:"the director",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'dirigere' (to direct). The top boss.\nIn German schools, the principal is also 'der Direktor.'",example:"A: Der Direktor möchte dich sprechen.\nB: Oh. Was will er?\nA: Keine Sorge. Er begrüßt alle neuen Mitarbeiter.\nB: Ah, gut. Dann gehe ich gleich hin.",exampleSrc:"A: The director wants to speak with you.\nB: Oh. What does he want?\nA: No worries. He welcomes all new employees.\nB: Ah, good. Then I will go right away.",funFact:"Direktor is more formal than Leiter. In German schools, the principal is 'der Direktor.' In companies, the Direktor sits at the top. 'Direktorsebene' (director level) is where the big decisions happen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Direktorin",src:"the director (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Germany has been increasing the number of Direktorinnen in leadership.\nThe -in suffix is mandatory when referring to a specific woman.",example:"A: Die Direktorin kommt um elf Uhr.\nB: Die neue Direktorin? Ich habe sie noch nicht kennengelernt.\nA: Sie wurde letzten Monat eingestellt.\nB: Ich bin gespannt auf die Besprechung.",exampleSrc:"A: The director is coming at eleven o'clock.\nB: The new director? I have not met her yet.\nA: She was hired last month.\nB: I am curious about the meeting.",funFact:"Germany has been steadily increasing the number of Direktorinnen in leadership positions. Since 2015, a Frauenquote (women's quota) requires large companies to have at least 30% women on their supervisory boards."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Leiter",src:"the ladder",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine. Der Leiter = male leader, die Leiter = ladder.\nGender changes meaning completely.",example:"A: Wo ist die Leiter? Ich muss an die Decke.\nB: Im Lager. Der Hausmeister hat sie.\nA: Danke. Die Leiter wird oft gebraucht.\nB: Ja, besonders wenn Lampen gewechselt werden.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the ladder? I need to reach the ceiling.\nB: In the storage room. The caretaker has it.\nA: Thanks. The ladder is often needed.\nB: Yes, especially when lamps are changed.",funFact:"Der Leiter (masculine) = leader. Die Leiter (feminine) = ladder. 'Die Karriereleiter' (career ladder) combines both meanings beautifully: you climb the Leiter to become a Leiter."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Liste",src:"the list",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Same word in many European languages.\nGermans make Listen for everything: Einkaufsliste, Aufgabenliste, Wunschliste.",example:"A: Steht das auf der Liste?\nB: Ja, Punkt sieben auf der Liste.\nA: Gut. Wir arbeiten die Liste ab.\nB: Bis Freitag muss alles auf der Liste erledigt sein.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that on the list?\nB: Yes, point seven on the list.\nA: Good. We will work through the list.\nB: By Friday everything on the list must be completed.",funFact:"Germans make Listen for everything: Einkaufsliste (shopping list), Aufgabenliste (task list), Wunschliste (wish list), Packliste (packing list). If it can be organized, it gets a Liste."},
{type:"fb",s:"Einen Termin {1} wir am besten heute.",a:["legen"],opts:["legen","setzen","stehen","halten"],hint:"The base form of a separable verb meaning to pin down or commit to a date. The sentence already shows the prefix at the end.",sSrc:"We should set the date today."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Organisation",src:"the organization",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"The -tion ending is always feminine in German.\nAlways stressed on the last syllable: Organisa-TION.",example:"A: Die Organisation der Konferenz war perfekt.\nB: Danke! Es wurde alles im Voraus geplant.\nA: Gute Organisation ist der Schlüssel zum Erfolg.\nB: Ja, ohne Organisation funktioniert nichts.",exampleSrc:"A: The organization of the conference was perfect.\nB: Thanks! Everything was planned in advance.\nA: Good organization is the key to success.\nB: Yes, without organization nothing works.",funFact:"The -tion ending is always feminine in German and always stressed on the last syllable: Organisa-TION. This rule works for Kommunikation, Information, Situation, and hundreds more. Free gender rule for all Latin loanwords."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Stil",src:"the style",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Same word in English. 'Führungsstil' = management style.\n'Arbeitsstil' = work style. 'Im großen Stil' = on a grand scale.",example:"A: Wie ist der Führungsstil hier?\nB: Ziemlich locker. Wir arbeiten selbstständig.\nA: Das passt zu meinem Arbeitsstil.\nB: Gut. Jeder hat seinen eigenen Stil.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the management style here?\nB: Pretty relaxed. We work independently.\nA: That suits my work style.\nB: Good. Everyone has their own style.",funFact:"Führungsstil (management style) is a key concept in German business culture. German companies are known for 'Mitbestimmung' (co-determination), where employees have a say in management decisions."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Loch",src:"the hole",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Plural: die Löcher. 'Ein Loch in der Wand.'\n'Budgetloch' = budget hole (deficit). 'Schwarzes Loch' = black hole.",example:"A: Da ist ein Loch in der Wand!\nB: Ja, dort hing vorher ein Regal.\nA: Das Loch muss repariert werden.\nB: Der Hausmeister wurde schon informiert.",exampleSrc:"A: There is a hole in the wall!\nB: Yes, a shelf used to hang there.\nA: The hole needs to be repaired.\nB: The caretaker was already informed.",funFact:"'Budgetloch' (budget hole) is what Germans call a deficit. 'Schwarzes Loch' is a black hole. 'Ein Loch im Socken' (a hole in the sock) is the morning nightmare. German uses Loch for any gap, literal or figurative."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Decke",src:"the ceiling, the blanket",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Two meanings: ceiling and blanket. Context decides.\n'An die Decke gehen' = to hit the ceiling (to get very angry).",example:"A: Die Decke im Büro ist sehr hoch.\nB: Ja, dreieinhalb Meter. Ein alter Bau.\nA: Und die Lampe an der Decke?\nB: Die wurde letzte Woche ausgetauscht.",exampleSrc:"A: The ceiling in the office is very high.\nB: Yes, three and a half meters. An old building.\nA: And the lamp on the ceiling?\nB: It was replaced last week.",funFact:"Decke means both ceiling and blanket. 'An die Decke gehen' (to go to the ceiling) means to get very angry. 'Unter einer Decke stecken' (to be under one blanket) means to be in cahoots."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kerze",src:"the candle",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Kerzen anzünden' = to light candles. Very German.\nBirthday tradition: one candle per year on the cake.",example:"A: Warum stehen Kerzen auf dem Tisch?\nB: Thomas hat Geburtstag. Eine Kerze für jedes Jahr.\nA: Das sind viele Kerzen!\nB: Ja, er wird fünfzig. Die Kerzen wurden alle angezündet.",exampleSrc:"A: Why are there candles on the table?\nB: Thomas has his birthday. One candle for each year.\nA: That is a lot of candles!\nB: Yes, he is turning fifty. The candles were all lit.",funFact:"Germans love candles. Germany is Europe's largest candle market. In winter, Adventskränze (Advent wreaths) have four candles. Birthday cakes have one candle per year of life. Candle-lit evenings are called 'gemütlich.'"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Auftrag",src:"the assignment"},{trg:"der Direktor",src:"the director (m)"},{trg:"die Direktorin",src:"the director (f)"},{trg:"die Leiter",src:"the ladder"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie heißt das Loch in der Decke, durch das Licht kommt?",opts:["Das große Dach der Halle","Die helle Kerze","Der besondere Stil des Raums","Die Decke hat ein Loch"],ans:"Die Decke hat ein Loch",hint:"The question describes an opening in the ceiling. Which option directly addresses this?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} der Konferenz war perfekt geplant.",a:["Organisation"],opts:["Organisation","Liste","Stil","Kerze"],hint:"The systematic planning and coordination of an event.",sSrc:"The organization of the conference was perfectly planned."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was steht auf deutschen Geschäftsbriefen vor der Unterschrift?",opts:["Im Auftrag von","Auf der Liste","Im Stil von","Mit dem Direktor"],ans:"Im Auftrag von",hint:"This abbreviation (i.A.) means someone is signing on behalf of another person."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Auftrag'?",opts:["the main director","the decorative style","the order, the task","the small hole"],ans:"the order, the task",hint:"Think of receiving instructions from a client or boss to complete a job."},
{type:"fb",s:"Auf der {1} stehen sieben Punkte für die Besprechung.",a:["Liste"],opts:["Liste","Decke","Kerze","Organisation"],hint:"A structured document with numbered items to work through.",sSrc:"There are seven points on the list for the meeting."}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Grammatik im Büro II ───
{id:"deu_r14l6",title:"Grammatik im Büro II",icon:"📝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Grammatik im Büro II",desc:"Seven essential office verbs plus two grammar powerhouses: the passive Präteritum and relative clauses. Learn to describe actions, clarify problems, and set deadlines.",goals:["Learn seven workplace action verbs","Master passive Präteritum: wurde + Partizip II","Build relative clauses with der/die/das"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"bedienen",src:"to operate, to serve",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + dienen (to serve). 'Eine Maschine bedienen' = to operate a machine.\n'Kunden bedienen' = to serve customers.",example:"A: Kannst du den Kopierer bedienen?\nB: Ja, er ist einfach zu bedienen.\nA: Zeig mir bitte, wie er bedient wird.\nB: Klar, drück diesen Knopf und warte.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you operate the copier?\nB: Yes, it is easy to operate.\nA: Please show me how it is operated.\nB: Sure, press this button and wait.",funFact:"Bedienen has two meanings: to operate a machine and to serve a customer. 'Selbstbedienung' (self-service) is everywhere in Germany. 'Wird hier bedient?' (Is there table service here?) is the first question in any restaurant."},
{type:"teach",trg:"klären",src:"to clarify, to settle",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From 'klar' (clear). 'Das müssen wir klären.'\nThe calm German way of saying 'we have a problem.'",example:"A: Es gibt ein Missverständnis. Das muss geklärt werden.\nB: Okay, was muss geklärt werden?\nA: Wer ist für das Projekt verantwortlich?\nB: Das wurde in der letzten Besprechung geklärt.",exampleSrc:"A: There is a misunderstanding. That needs to be clarified.\nB: Okay, what needs to be clarified?\nA: Who is responsible for the project?\nB: That was clarified in the last meeting.",funFact:"'Das müssen wir klären' (we need to clarify that) is the calm German way of saying 'we have a problem.' Klären comes from klar (clear). A Kläranlage is a water treatment plant that 'clarifies' dirty water."},
{type:"teach",trg:"festlegen",src:"to determine, to establish, to set",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fest (firm) + legen (to lay). 'Einen Termin festlegen.'\nThe fest- prefix family: festhalten, festsetzen, feststehen, festlegen.",example:"A: Wann legen wir den Termin fest?\nB: Am besten heute. Der Termin wurde noch nicht festgelegt.\nA: Wie wäre es mit nächstem Dienstag?\nB: Gut. Dann legen wir Dienstag fest.",exampleSrc:"A: When do we set the date?\nB: Best today. The date has not been set yet.\nA: How about next Tuesday?\nB: Good. Then we will set Tuesday.",funFact:"The fest- prefix family all mean making something firm or fixed: festlegen (to establish), festhalten (to hold on to), festsetzen (to fix/determine), feststehen (to be certain). All built from fest (firm)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"festsetzen",src:"to fix, to set, to determine",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fest (firm) + setzen (to set). More official than festlegen.\n'Der Preis wurde festgesetzt' = the price was fixed.",example:"A: Der Termin wurde auf Freitag festgesetzt.\nB: Von wem?\nA: Von der Direktorin. Das steht fest.\nB: Okay, dann muss ich meinen Terminkalender ändern.",exampleSrc:"A: The date was set for Friday.\nB: By whom?\nA: By the director. That is certain.\nB: Okay, then I need to change my schedule.",funFact:"Festsetzen is more official than festlegen. Prices are festgesetzt, court dates are festgesetzt, rules are festgesetzt. It implies authority made the decision."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das müssen wir klären.' Was bedeutet klären?",opts:["to clean","to clarify/settle","to fix a date","to record"],ans:"to clarify/settle",hint:"From 'klar' (clear). The calm German way of saying 'we have a problem.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"feststehen",src:"to be certain, to be definite",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fest + stehen (to stand). 'Das steht fest' = that is certain.\nSomething that festststeht cannot be changed.",example:"A: Steht der Termin fest?\nB: Ja, das steht fest. Nächsten Mittwoch.\nA: Gut. Das steht also fest.\nB: Ja, es wurde von der Leitung festgelegt.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the date definite?\nB: Yes, that is certain. Next Wednesday.\nA: Good. So that is definite.\nB: Yes, it was determined by management.",funFact:"'Das steht fest' is one of the most decisive phrases in German. When something festststeht, discussion is over. It combines fest (firm) with stehen (to stand): it stands firm. No arguments."},
{type:"teach",trg:"festhalten",src:"to hold on to, to record, to note",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fest + halten (to hold). Physical: 'Halt dich fest!'\nAbstract: 'Wir halten das im Protokoll fest' (record in minutes).",example:"A: Halte bitte fest, was in der Besprechung besprochen wird.\nB: Natürlich. Ich schreibe alles auf.\nA: Gut. Das muss im Protokoll festgehalten werden.\nB: Wird gemacht.",exampleSrc:"A: Please record what is discussed in the meeting.\nB: Of course. I will write everything down.\nA: Good. That must be recorded in the minutes.\nB: Will be done.",funFact:"Festhalten means both physical holding (Halt dich fest! = Hold on tight!) and recording (im Protokoll festhalten = record in the minutes). German meetings always produce a Protokoll where everything is festgehalten."},
{type:"teach",trg:"inner",src:"inner, internal",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Die innere Stimme' = the inner voice.\n'Innerbetrieblich' = within the company.",example:"A: Die innere Organisation muss verbessert werden.\nB: Ja, die inneren Abläufe sind zu langsam.\nA: Das wurde auch in der Besprechung besprochen.\nB: Wir klären das nächste Woche.",exampleSrc:"A: The internal organization must be improved.\nB: Yes, the internal processes are too slow.\nA: That was also discussed in the meeting.\nB: We will clarify that next week.",funFact:"Inner describes anything inside: innere Stimme (inner voice), innere Ruhe (inner peace), Innenminister (interior minister). 'Innere Werte' (inner values) is what Germans say matters more than appearances."},
{type:"tip",title:"Passiv Präteritum: wurde + Partizip II",text:"Past passive: something WAS done.\nEnglish: 'The office was built in 2010.'\nGerman: 'Das Büro wurde 2010 gebaut.'\n\nThe past passive is formed with a conjugated form of wurde plus a Partizip II at the end.\n\nWurde is the Präteritum of werden:\n- ich wurde, du wurdest, er/sie/es wurde\n- wir wurden, ihr wurdet, sie/Sie wurden\n\nCompare the two tenses:\n- wird gemacht (IS being made, Präsens)\n- wurde gemacht (WAS made, Präteritum)\n\nPassiv Präteritum is standard in written German for reporting past events.",deepDive:{title:"Passiv mit 'von' und 'durch'",text:"Who did the action? Two prepositions help:\n\n'von + Dativ' identifies a person:\nDer Bericht wurde von der Leiterin geschrieben.\n(The report was written by the manager.)\n\n'durch + Akkusativ' identifies a means:\nDie Nachricht wurde durch eine E-Mail gesendet.\n(The message was sent by means of an email.)\n\nVon = who did it (agent)\nDurch = how it was done (means)"}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Passiv Präteritum: wurde + Partizip II",groups:[{label:"Singular",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"wurde eingeladen",src:"I was invited"},{pronoun:"du",form:"wurdest eingeladen",src:"you were invited"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"wurde eingeladen",src:"he/she/it was invited"}]},{label:"Plural",rows:[{pronoun:"wir",form:"wurden eingeladen",src:"we were invited"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"wurdet eingeladen",src:"you (pl.) were invited"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"wurden eingeladen",src:"they/you (formal) were invited"}]}],note:"Wurde replaces wird. Past participle stays at the end."},
{type:"tip",title:"ge- or no ge-? Partizip II Rules",text:"Regular verbs add ge- at the start and -t at the end:\n- gemacht, gekauft, gelernt\n\nIrregular verbs add ge- but change the stem and end in -en:\n- geschrieben, gesprochen, gelesen\n\nInseparable prefixes (be-, ver-, er-, ent-, emp-, zer-) get NO ge-:\n- bezahlt, verkauft, erklärt, entdeckt\n\nVerbs ending in -ieren also get NO ge-:\n- repariert, studiert, organisiert",deepDive:{title:"Separable Prefixes and ge-",text:"With separable verbs, ge- goes BETWEEN prefix and stem:\naufgemacht, zugemacht, eingeladen, angefangen\n\naufmachen: aufgemacht\neinladen: eingeladen\nmitbringen: mitgebracht\n\nSeparable prefixes: auf, an, ein, mit, aus, ab, zu, vor\nInseparable prefixes: be-, ge-, er-, ver-, zer-, ent-, emp-, miss-"}},
{type:"tip",title:"worden vs. geworden",text:"Passive Perfekt: ist gemacht WORDEN (NOT geworden!)\n\ngeworden = became (full verb 'werden'):\nEr ist Arzt geworden. (He became a doctor.)\n\nworden = passive auxiliary:\nEs ist gebaut worden. (It has been built.)\n\nRule: In passive Perfekt, 'geworden' is shortened to 'worden.'",deepDive:{title:"Process Passive vs. State Passive",text:"Process passive (werden + PP) = ACTION:\nDas Fenster wird geöffnet.\n(Someone is opening it right now.)\n\nState passive (sein + PP) = RESULT:\nDas Fenster ist geöffnet.\n(It is in an open state.)\n\nThe difference:\nwird geöffnet = process\nist geöffnet = result\n\nThis distinction is tested on the Goethe B1 exam."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das Büro wurde 2010 gebaut.' Wann wurde das Büro gebaut?",opts:["Es wird nächstes Jahr gebaut","Es wird jetzt gebaut","Im Jahr 2010","Es hat schon immer existiert"],ans:"Im Jahr 2010",hint:"Wurde + Partizip = Passiv Vergangenheit. The action is finished."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Konferenz {1} gestern organisiert.",a:["wurde"],opts:["wurde","wird","werden","wurden"],hint:"The conference (singular) WAS organized yesterday. Past passive singular.",sSrc:"The conference was organized yesterday."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher Satz beschreibt etwas, das JETZT passiert?",opts:["Die Datei wird kopiert.","Die Datei wurde kopiert.","Die Datei war kopiert worden.","Die Datei ist kopiert worden."],ans:"Die Datei wird kopiert.",hint:"Which option uses present tense passive? One auxiliary signals a current action; another signals a completed one."},
{type:"tip",title:"Relative Clauses: der/die/das as Relative Pronouns",text:"Relative clauses describe a noun.\n'The colleague WHO sits next to me' = 'Der Kollege, DER neben mir sitzt.'\n\nThe relative pronoun agrees with:\nGENDER and NUMBER of the reference word\nbut the CASE depends on its role in the relative clause.\n\nNominative (subject): der/die/das/die\nAccusative (object): den/die/das/die\nDative (indirect object): dem/der/dem/denen\n\nThe verb goes to the END of the relative clause.\nComma before the relative pronoun is mandatory.",deepDive:{title:"Relative Clauses in the Office",text:"Relative clauses are perfect for descriptions:\n\nDer Kollege, der neben mir sitzt, heißt Thomas.\n(Nominative: he sits)\n\nDie Datei, die ich gestern kopiert habe, ist weg.\n(Accusative: I copied IT)\n\nDer Kollege, dem ich das Dokument gegeben habe, ist krank.\n(Dative: I gave it TO HIM)\n\nTip: Gender from the reference word. Case from the role in the subclause. Verb at end. Comma before.\n\nIMPORTANT: Relative clauses in German ALWAYS need commas (not optional like in English).\n\nNominative or accusative? The test:\nWho performs the action in the relative clause?\nDer Mann, der singt = HE sings (nominative).\nDer Mann, den ich sehe = I see HIM (accusative).\nOnly MASCULINE changes: der to den.\n\nCommon dative verbs in relative clauses:\nhelfen, danken, gefallen, gehören, vertrauen, folgen\nAll require dem/der/dem/denen.\n\n'was' as relative pronoun:\nAfter alles, etwas, nichts, vieles, einiges: Alles, was er sagt...\nAfter neuter superlatives: Das Beste, was ich je gegessen habe...\nAfter whole sentences: Er lacht, was mich freut."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Relativpronomen: der/die/das",groups:[{label:"Nominativ (Subjekt)",rows:[{pronoun:"maskulin",form:"der",src:"who/that (m)"},{pronoun:"feminin",form:"die",src:"who/that (f)"},{pronoun:"neutrum",form:"das",src:"who/that (n)"},{pronoun:"Plural",form:"die",src:"who/that (pl)"}]},{label:"Akkusativ (direktes Objekt)",rows:[{pronoun:"maskulin",form:"den",src:"whom/that (m)"},{pronoun:"feminin",form:"die",src:"whom/that (f)"},{pronoun:"neutrum",form:"das",src:"whom/that (n)"},{pronoun:"Plural",form:"die",src:"whom/that (pl)"}]},{label:"Dativ (indirektes Objekt)",rows:[{pronoun:"maskulin",form:"dem",src:"to whom (m)"},{pronoun:"feminin",form:"der",src:"to whom (f)"},{pronoun:"neutrum",form:"dem",src:"to whom (n)"},{pronoun:"Plural",form:"denen",src:"to whom (pl)"}]}],note:"Gender from the reference word. Case from the role in the relative clause. Verb at end."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Mein Kollege, ___ neben mir sitzt, heißt Thomas.' Welches Relativpronomen passt?",opts:["die (falsch)","dem","den","der"],ans:"der",hint:"Kollege is masculine. In the relative clause, he IS SITTING (subject position)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Eine Datei, {1} ich gestern kopiert habe, ist weg.",a:["die"],opts:["die","der","das","den"],hint:"Datei is feminine. In the relative clause, I copied IT (direct object = accusative).",sSrc:"A file that I copied yesterday is gone."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Der Kollege, ___ ich das Dokument gegeben habe, ist im Urlaub.' Welches Pronomen?",opts:["dem","den (falsch)","die","der"],ans:"dem",hint:"Kollege is masculine. I gave the document TO HIM (indirect object = Dativ)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher Satz kombiniert Passiv UND Relativsatz?",opts:["Der Tisch, der neu ist, steht hier.","Das Dokument liegt auf dem Tisch.","Das Dokument, das gestern gedruckt wurde, liegt auf dem Tisch.","Gestern wurde das Dokument gedruckt."],ans:"Das Dokument, das gestern gedruckt wurde, liegt auf dem Tisch.",hint:"Find the sentence where a passive construction appears inside the relative clause, marked by commas around it."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Büros {1} letztes Jahr renoviert.",a:["wurden"],opts:["wurden","wurde","wird","werden"],hint:"Multiple offices (plural) WERE renovated. Plural past passive.",sSrc:"The offices were renovated last year."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Die Kollegin, {1} gestern {2} wurde, heißt Anna.",blanks:{"1":"die","2":"eingeladen"},pool:["die","der","eingeladen","einladen","dem","wurde"],hint:"Kollegin is feminine. She WAS invited (accusative passive). Feminine accusative relative pronoun = die.",sSrc:"The colleague who was invited yesterday is called Anna."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das Kind, ___ wir geholfen haben, war dankbar.' Welches Pronomen?",opts:["das","dem","den","die"],ans:"dem",hint:"Kind is neuter. Helfen governs dative: we helped IT. Think neuter dative."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Der Auftrag, {1} letzte Woche {2} wurde, ist jetzt {3}.",blanks:{"1":"der","2":"erledigt","3":"fertig"},pool:["der","den","erledigt","erledigen","fertig","wurde"],hint:"Auftrag is masculine, subject of the relative clause (Nominativ). It WAS completed.",sSrc:"The assignment that was completed last week is now finished."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"anxious",art:"de-ber-office-hallway",trg:"Gleich ist die Besprechung. Mia hat gesagt, ich soll alle siezen. Aber was, wenn ich es vergesse? Was, wenn mir ein 'du' rausrutscht?",src:"The meeting is coming up. Mia said I should use Sie with everyone. But what if I forget? What if a du slips out?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Der Termin ist fix und unveränderlich. Ja, das ___ fest. Nächsten Mittwoch.",opts:["liegt","steht","hält","legt"],ans:"steht",hint:"A separable verb combining fest (firm) with stehen. Something that cannot be changed."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Es steht fest, dass wir nächste Woche umziehen.' Was bedeutet 'feststehen'?",opts:["to be fixed, settled","to stand still, freeze","to hold on to something","to remain seated firmly"],ans:"to be fixed, settled",hint:"Fest (firm) + stehen (stand). When something stands firm, it will not change anymore."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 5: Du oder Sie? ───
{id:"deu_r14l7",title:"Du oder Sie?",icon:"🤝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Du oder Sie?",desc:"Verumius accidentally says 'du' to the department head in a meeting. Silence. Then a smile. Learn to navigate the Du/Sie minefield.",goals:["Navigate the Du/Sie minefield in a German office","Practice passive and relative clauses in real work situations","Survive your first Besprechung (meeting)"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"tense",art:"de-ber-meeting-room",trg:"Es ist zehn Uhr. Verumius sitzt im Besprechungsraum. Die Abteilungsleiterin, die alle nur 'Frau Müller' nennen, betritt den Raum.",src:"It is ten o'clock. Verumius sits in the meeting room. The department head, whom everyone only calls 'Frau Müller,' enters the room."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"nervous",art:"de-ber-meeting-room",trg:"Guten Morgen! Ah... du hast... ich meine... Sie haben... die Präsentation schon vorbereitet?",src:"Good morning! Ah... you have (informal)... I mean... you have (formal)... already prepared the presentation?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"dramatic",art:"de-ber-meeting-room",trg:"Stille. Mias Augen werden groß. Die Kollegen schauen auf ihre Laptops. Dann lächelt Frau Müller.",src:"Silence. Mia's eyes go wide. The colleagues look at their laptops. Then Frau Müller smiles."},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"relieved",art:"de-ber-meeting-room",trg:"'Sie können ruhig du sagen,' sagt Frau Müller. 'Wir duzen uns hier alle.' Verumius atmet aus.",src:"'You can go ahead and say du,' says Frau Müller. 'We all use du with each other here.' Verumius exhales."},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"conspiratorial",art:"de-ber-office-hallway",trg:"Aber Vorsicht mit Kunden. Kunden werden gesiezt. Immer. Manche Hamburger Firmen benutzen das 'Hamburger Sie': Vorname plus Sie. 'Anna, können Sie mir die Datei schicken?'",src:"But careful with clients. Clients are addressed with Sie. Always. Some Hamburg companies use the 'Hamburger Sie': first name plus Sie. 'Anna, can you send me the file?'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"duzen",src:"to use 'du' (informal) with someone",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Wir duzen uns' = we address each other informally.\nThe older or higher-ranking person always offers first.",example:"A: Darf ich Sie duzen?\nB: Natürlich! Wir duzen uns hier alle.\nA: Gut. Dann sage ich ab jetzt du.\nB: Perfekt. Ich bin Thomas.",exampleSrc:"A: May I use 'du' with you?\nB: Of course! We all use 'du' with each other here.\nA: Good. Then I will say 'du' from now on.\nB: Perfect. I am Thomas.",funFact:"Offering the 'du' is a social milestone in Germany. The older or higher-ranking person always offers first. 'Wollen wir uns duzen?' (Shall we use du?) is a significant moment in any relationship."},
{type:"teach",trg:"siezen",src:"to use 'Sie' (formal) with someone",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Default with strangers, officials, and in business.\nBreaking through to 'du' can take years.",example:"A: Siezen Sie mich bitte.\nB: Natürlich, kein Problem.\nA: Wir siezen uns im Büro mit allen Kunden.\nB: Verstehe. Hier wird gesiezt, nicht geduzt.",exampleSrc:"A: Please use 'Sie' with me.\nB: Of course, no problem.\nA: We use 'Sie' with all clients in the office.\nB: I understand. Here we use formal address, not informal.",funFact:"The default with strangers, officials, and in business is Sie. Breaking through to 'du' can take years in some relationships. Some neighbors siezen each other for decades. It is not unfriendly, it is respectful."},
{type:"teach",trg:"klopfen",src:"to knock",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Onomatopoeia. Germans ALWAYS knock before entering an office.\n'Bitte klopfen' is on many office doors. Three knocks is standard.",example:"A: Klopf bitte an, bevor du reinkommst.\nB: Natürlich. Ich klopfe immer an.\nA: Gut. In diesem Büro wird angeklopft.\nB: Verstanden. Drei Mal klopfen?",exampleSrc:"A: Please knock before you come in.\nB: Of course. I always knock.\nA: Good. In this office, knocking is expected.\nB: Understood. Three knocks?",funFact:"Germans ALWAYS knock before entering an office. 'Bitte klopfen' (please knock) is on many office doors. Three knocks is the standard. Entering without knocking is considered extremely rude."},
{type:"teach",trg:"klingeln",src:"to ring",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Onomatopoeia. 'Es klingelt' = the bell/phone is ringing.\nYour phone klingelt, your doorbell klingelt.",example:"A: Es klingelt! Wer ist da?\nB: Wahrscheinlich der Postbote. Er klingelt jeden Tag.\nA: Soll ich aufmachen?\nB: Ja, bitte. Er hat ein Paket.",exampleSrc:"A: The bell is ringing! Who is there?\nB: Probably the mailman. He rings every day.\nA: Should I open up?\nB: Yes, please. He has a package.",funFact:"German has many sound-words: klingeln (to ring), klopfen (to knock), klirren (to clink), knacken (to crack). German onomatopoeia is surprisingly precise."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Klingel",src:"the bell, the doorbell",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Every German apartment building has a row of Klingeln with name tags.\nFinding the right Klingel is the first challenge for visitors.",example:"A: Wo ist die Klingel für die dritte Etage?\nB: Die dritte von oben. Steht 'Schmidt' drauf.\nA: Ah, ich sehe sie. Die Klingel ist sehr klein.\nB: Ja, aber sie funktioniert.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the doorbell for the third floor?\nB: The third from the top. It says 'Schmidt' on it.\nA: Ah, I see it. The bell is very small.\nB: Yes, but it works.",funFact:"Every German apartment building has a row of Klingeln with name tags. If your name is not on the Klingel, the Postbote will not deliver your packages. First rule after moving in: put your name on the Klingel."},
{type:"fb",s:"In Deutschland {1} man immer an, bevor man ein Büro betritt.",a:["klopft"],opts:["klopft","klingelt","schaltet","dreht"],hint:"Three times on the door before entering. A basic German office courtesy.",sSrc:"In Germany you always knock before entering an office."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einschalten",src:"to turn on, to switch on",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ein- (on) + schalten (to switch). Separable verb.\nOpposite: ausschalten (to turn off).",example:"A: Kannst du den Computer einschalten?\nB: Natürlich. Er wird gerade eingeschaltet.\nA: Dauert das immer so lange?\nB: Ja, der Rechner ist alt. Er wurde nie ausgetauscht.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you turn on the computer?\nB: Of course. It is being turned on right now.\nA: Does it always take this long?\nB: Yes, the computer is old. It was never replaced.",funFact:"Einschalten and ausschalten (on/off) are the most basic German tech verbs. 'Haben Sie versucht, ihn aus- und wieder einzuschalten?' (Have you tried turning it off and on again?) is the universal IT helpdesk answer."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schalten",src:"to switch, to shift",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"The base verb. 'Den Gang schalten' = to shift gears.\n'Schalter' = switch. 'Schaltjahr' = leap year (a switched year).",example:"A: Wie schalte ich den Drucker ein?\nB: Da ist ein Schalter auf der Seite.\nA: Dieser kleine Knopf hier?\nB: Genau. Einmal schalten und warten.",exampleSrc:"A: How do I switch on the printer?\nB: There is a switch on the side.\nA: This little button here?\nB: Exactly. Switch once and wait.",funFact:"Schalten gives us Schalter (switch), Schaltjahr (leap year, literally 'switch year'), and Schaltfläche (digital button). Gang schalten means to shift gears in a car. Most German cars still have manual Schaltgetriebe."},
{type:"teach",trg:"drehen",src:"to turn, to rotate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Physical rotation. 'Einen Film drehen' = to shoot a film.\n'Sich drehen' = to turn around.",example:"A: Dreh den Knopf nach rechts.\nB: So? Passiert nichts.\nA: Noch etwas weiter drehen.\nB: Ah, jetzt funktioniert es!",exampleSrc:"A: Turn the knob to the right.\nB: Like this? Nothing is happening.\nA: Turn a bit more.\nB: Ah, now it works!",funFact:"'Einen Film drehen' (to turn a film) means to shoot a movie. It comes from physically turning the film reel in old cameras. 'Mir dreht sich alles' (everything is turning for me) means being dizzy."},
{type:"teach",trg:"heizen",src:"to heat",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Die Heizung' = the heating system. 'Heizkosten' = heating costs.\nGermans are very conscious of Heizkosten.",example:"A: Wird das Büro im Winter geheizt?\nB: Natürlich. Die Heizung wird im Oktober eingeschaltet.\nA: Und die Heizkosten?\nB: Die werden vom Betrieb bezahlt.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the office heated in winter?\nB: Of course. The heating is turned on in October.\nA: And the heating costs?\nB: They are paid by the company.",funFact:"Germans are very conscious of Heizkosten (heating costs). 'Heiz nicht so viel!' (Do not heat so much!) is a common household complaint. The Heizkostenabrechnung (heating cost bill) arrives once a year and causes stress."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"klingeln",src:"to ring"},{trg:"die Klingel",src:"the doorbell"},{trg:"schalten",src:"to switch"},{trg:"drehen",src:"to turn/rotate"}]},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"duzen",src:"to use 'du' with someone"},{trg:"siezen",src:"to use 'Sie' with someone"},{trg:"klopfen",src:"to knock"},{trg:"klingeln",src:"to ring"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Heizung wird im Oktober eingeschaltet.' Was passiert im Oktober?",opts:["Die Heizung wird angemacht","Die Heizung wird repariert","Die Heizung wird abgeschaltet","Die Heizung geht kaputt"],ans:"Die Heizung wird angemacht",hint:"Einschalten means to turn on. The heating is activated at the start of the cold season."}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Technik und Einrichtung ───
{id:"deu_r14l8",title:"Technik und Einrichtung",icon:"💡",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Technik und Einrichtung",desc:"From sending emails to furnishing offices, from stamps to armchairs: master the vocabulary of modern German workplaces and living spaces.",goals:["Learn technology and office equipment vocabulary","Describe furniture and room features","Use passive and relative clauses with tech vocabulary"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"senden",src:"to send, to broadcast",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"More formal than 'schicken.' 'Eine E-Mail senden.'\nAlso: 'Der Sender sendet ein Signal' (broadcast).",example:"A: Wurde die E-Mail schon gesendet?\nB: Ja, sie wurde heute Morgen gesendet.\nA: Gut. Dann warten wir auf die Antwort.\nB: Die wird sicher bald kommen.",exampleSrc:"A: Has the email been sent yet?\nB: Yes, it was sent this morning.\nA: Good. Then we wait for the reply.\nB: It will surely come soon.",funFact:"Senden has two past participles: 'gesendet' (for sending messages) and 'gesandt' (more literary, for sending people). In the office, 'gesendet' is standard. 'Die E-Mail wurde gesendet' is the confirmation you want to see."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Knopf",src:"the button (physical), the knob",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Auf den Knopf drücken' = to press the button.\nAlso means a button on clothing. Not for digital screen buttons.",example:"A: Wo ist der Knopf für den Aufzug?\nB: Der große runde Knopf an der Wand.\nA: Dieser hier? Er leuchtet nicht.\nB: Drück fester. Der Knopf ist etwas alt.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the button for the elevator?\nB: The big round button on the wall.\nA: This one? It does not light up.\nB: Press harder. The button is a bit old.",funFact:"Knopf means both a mechanical button and a button on clothing. 'Knopfdruck' (button press) is used metaphorically: 'auf Knopfdruck' means at the push of a button, instantly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Klick",src:"the click",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From English. 'Ein Klick genügt' = one click is enough.\n'Doppelklick' = double click.",example:"A: Wie öffne ich die Datei?\nB: Mit einem Doppelklick.\nA: Ein Klick reicht nicht?\nB: Nein, für Dateien brauchst du zwei Klicks.",exampleSrc:"A: How do I open the file?\nB: With a double click.\nA: One click is not enough?\nB: No, for files you need two clicks.",funFact:"Klick is borrowed from English. 'Ein-Klick-Kauf' (one-click purchase) changed online shopping. In German, Klick can also mean a sudden understanding: 'Es hat Klick gemacht' (it clicked, I understood)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Stempel",src:"the stamp, the seal",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Germany runs on Stempel. Official documents need an official stamp.\n'Abgestempelt' = stamped, but also 'labeled/stigmatized.'",example:"A: Braucht dieses Dokument einen Stempel?\nB: Ja, ohne Stempel ist es nicht gültig.\nA: Wo bekomme ich den Stempel?\nB: Bei der Sekretärin. Sie hat den Firmenstempel.",exampleSrc:"A: Does this document need a stamp?\nB: Yes, without a stamp it is not valid.\nA: Where do I get the stamp?\nB: From the secretary. She has the company stamp.",funFact:"Germany runs on Stempel (stamps). Official documents, contracts, certifications all need a Stempel to be valid. 'Abgestempelt werden' also means to be labeled or stigmatized, to have a metaphorical stamp put on you."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Sekretär",src:"the secretary (male), the writing desk",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Two meanings: male secretary AND a type of writing desk.\nThe furniture Sekretär is an antique desk with a fold-down front.",example:"A: Herr Weber ist der Sekretär der Geschäftsleitung.\nB: Seit wann?\nA: Seit zwei Jahren. Vorher war er in der IT.\nB: Ein interessanter Karrierewechsel.",exampleSrc:"A: Herr Weber is the secretary of the executive board.\nB: Since when?\nA: For two years. Before that he was in IT.\nB: An interesting career change.",funFact:"Sekretär has two meanings: male secretary AND a type of antique writing desk with a fold-down front. The furniture meaning comes from French and refers to a desk where secrets (sekret) were kept."},
{type:"mc",q:"Dieses Dokument braucht einen offiziellen Abdruck. Wie heißt das?",opts:["der Mausklick","der Druckknopf","der Stempel","der Lautsprecher"],ans:"der Stempel",hint:"An official seal that makes documents legally valid. Germany runs on these."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Sitz",src:"the seat, the headquarters",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Firmensitz' = company headquarters. 'Sitzplatz' = seating place.\n'Seinen Sitz haben' = to be headquartered.",example:"A: Wo hat die Firma ihren Sitz?\nB: In Berlin-Mitte. Das ist der Hauptsitz.\nA: Und andere Standorte?\nB: Ja, einen Sitz in Hamburg und einen in München.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the company headquartered?\nB: In Berlin-Mitte. That is the headquarters.\nA: And other locations?\nB: Yes, one office in Hamburg and one in Munich.",funFact:"Sitz means both a physical seat and a headquarters. 'Firmensitz' is where the company is officially registered. 'Regierungssitz' (government seat) is Berlin for Germany. The Bundestag has its Sitz in the Reichstag building."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Sessel",src:"the armchair",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"A comfortable chair with armrests. More cozy than 'Stuhl' (chair).\nThe Büro-Sessel is the office desk chair.",example:"A: Der Sessel im Konferenzraum ist sehr bequem.\nB: Ja, die Sessel wurden neu gekauft.\nA: Viel besser als die alten Stühle.\nB: Die alten Stühle wurden letzten Monat entsorgt.",exampleSrc:"A: The armchair in the conference room is very comfortable.\nB: Yes, the armchairs were newly purchased.\nA: Much better than the old chairs.\nB: The old chairs were disposed of last month.",funFact:"In Austria, Sessel means any chair, not just armchairs. In Germany, a Sessel is specifically a comfortable armchair. The word comes from Latin 'sessio' (sitting). A Chefsessel is the boss's chair."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Kissen",src:"the cushion, the pillow",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Kopfkissen' = pillow. 'Sofakissen' = couch cushion.\nSome German offices have Kissen on chairs for comfort.",example:"A: Möchtest du ein Kissen für den Stuhl?\nB: Ja, gerne. Der Stuhl ist etwas hart.\nA: Hier, dieses Kissen ist weich.\nB: Danke, das ist viel besser.",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like a cushion for the chair?\nB: Yes, please. The chair is a bit hard.\nA: Here, this cushion is soft.\nB: Thanks, that is much better.",funFact:"Kopfkissen (head cushion) is a pillow. Sofakissen (sofa cushion) is a throw pillow. Germans have specific compound nouns for each type of Kissen. 'Kissenschlacht' (pillow fight) is one of the most fun German compounds."},
{type:"teach",trg:"mobil",src:"mobile",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Mobiles Arbeiten' = mobile working/remote work.\n'Mobiltelefon' is the formal word for cell phone, but everyone says 'Handy.'",example:"A: Arbeitest du mobil oder im Büro?\nB: Meistens mobil. Ich brauche nur meinen Laptop.\nA: Mobiles Arbeiten wird hier unterstützt.\nB: Ja, dreimal pro Woche ist mobiles Arbeiten erlaubt.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you work mobile or in the office?\nB: Mostly mobile. I only need my laptop.\nA: Mobile working is supported here.\nB: Yes, three times per week mobile working is allowed.",funFact:"'Mobiles Arbeiten' (mobile working/remote work) became standard in Germany after 2020. 'Mobiltelefon' is the formal word for cell phone, but everyone just says 'Handy,' a word that does not exist in English with this meaning."},
{type:"teach",trg:"möbliert",src:"furnished",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Möbel' (furniture). 'Möblierte Wohnung' = furnished apartment.\n'Möbliertes Zimmer' is common in German housing ads.",example:"A: Ist das Büro schon möbliert?\nB: Teilweise. Die Schreibtische sind da.\nA: Und die Regale?\nB: Die werden nächste Woche geliefert. Dann ist es voll möbliert.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the office already furnished?\nB: Partially. The desks are there.\nA: And the shelves?\nB: They will be delivered next week. Then it will be fully furnished.",funFact:"'Möbliertes Zimmer' (furnished room) is the most searched housing term for newcomers in Germany. Unmöbliert (unfurnished) in Germany means truly empty: no kitchen, no light fixtures, sometimes not even a kitchen sink."},
{type:"teach",trg:"elektrisch",src:"electric, electrical",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Elektrischer Strom' = electric current.\n'Elektroauto' = electric car. A big topic in Germany.",example:"A: Ist die Heizung elektrisch?\nB: Nein, wir heizen mit Gas.\nA: Und der Firmenwagen?\nB: Der ist elektrisch. Ein Elektroauto.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the heating electric?\nB: No, we heat with gas.\nA: And the company car?\nB: It is electric. An electric car.",funFact:"Germany's Energiewende (energy transition) is pushing everything to become elektrisch. Elektroautos, elektrische Busse, elektrische Roller. The word 'elektrisch' comes from Greek 'elektron' (amber), which produces static electricity when rubbed."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius sagt versehentlich 'du' zur Chefin. Wer bietet in der deutschen Bürokultur das 'du' zuerst an?",opts:["Jeder kann zuerst anbieten","Es passiert automatisch nach einem Monat","Die ranghöhere oder ältere Person","Der neue Mitarbeiter muss zuerst fragen"],ans:"Die ranghöhere oder ältere Person",hint:"Hierarchy and age determine who breaks the formal barrier in Germany."},
{type:"fb",s:"In unserem Büro {1} jeden Morgen eine Besprechung gehalten.",a:["wird"],opts:["wird","wurde","werden","worden"],hint:"A meeting IS held every morning. Present passive, singular.",sSrc:"In our office a meeting is held every morning."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Meine Kollegin, ___ neben Verumius sitzt, heißt Mia.' Welches Pronomen?",opts:["den (falsch)","dem","die","der"],ans:"die",hint:"Kollegin is feminine. She IS SITTING (subject position). Feminine subject form is needed."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Rechner, {1} ich bediene, ist neu.",a:["den"],opts:["den","der","dem","das"],hint:"Rechner is masculine. I operate IT (direct object = accusative). Think masculine accusative.",sSrc:"The computer that I operate is new."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Besprechung wurde um zehn Uhr begonnen.' Was ist passiert?",opts:["Die Besprechung beginnt um zehn","Die Besprechung wurde um zehn gestartet","Die Besprechung findet nicht statt","Die Besprechung wird um zehn beginnen"],ans:"Die Besprechung wurde um zehn gestartet",hint:"The meeting already started at ten. Find the option that places the action firmly in the past using the correct passive construction."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Die E-Mail, {1} gestern {2} wurde, ist wichtig.",blanks:{"1":"die","2":"gesendet"},pool:["die","der","gesendet","senden","wurde","wird"],hint:"E-Mail is feminine (direct object inside passive relative clause = Akkusativ). She WAS sent.",sSrc:"The email that was sent yesterday is important."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius klopft an die Tür, bevor er das Büro betritt. Warum klopft er?",opts:["Es ist höfliche Büro-Etikette in Deutschland","Die Tür ist meistens abgeschlossen","Jemand hat ihm gesagt, er soll immer klopfen","Er hat seinen Schlüssel vergessen"],ans:"Es ist höfliche Büro-Etikette in Deutschland",hint:"Knocking before entering is standard German office behavior everywhere."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Computer muss zuerst {1} werden.",a:["eingeschaltet"],opts:["eingeschaltet","einschalten","schalten","geschaltet"],hint:"The computer must be turned on. Modal passive: muss + Partizip II + werden.",sSrc:"The computer must first be turned on."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"duzen",src:"to use 'du' (informal)"},{trg:"siezen",src:"to use 'Sie' (formal)"},{trg:"klopfen",src:"to knock"},{trg:"einschalten",src:"to turn on"}]},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Der Kollege, {1} mich {2} hat, {3} gestern eingestellt.",blanks:{"1":"der","2":"begrüßt","3":"wurde"},pool:["der","den","begrüßt","begrüßen","wurde","wird"],hint:"Masculine colleague WHO (Nominativ) greeted me. He WAS hired yesterday (Passiv Präteritum).",sSrc:"The colleague who greeted me was hired yesterday."},
{type:"fb",s:"Dieses Dokument braucht einen {1}, sonst ist es nicht gültig.",a:["Stempel"],opts:["Stempel","Knopf","Klick","Sitz"],hint:"An official seal or stamp that makes documents legally valid.",sSrc:"This document needs a stamp, otherwise it is not valid."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'möbliert'?",opts:["leer und uneingerichtet","elektronisch vernetzt","repariert und erneuert","eingerichtet mit Möbeln"],ans:"eingerichtet mit Möbeln",hint:"This adjective describes a room or apartment that comes with furniture already inside."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Knopf",src:"the button/knob"},{trg:"der Sessel",src:"the armchair"},{trg:"das Kissen",src:"the cushion"},{trg:"mobil",src:"mobile"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"relieved",art:"de-ber-meeting-room",trg:"Die Besprechung ist vorbei. Verumius hat überlebt. Sogar Frau Müller hat gelächelt. In diesem Büro wird geduzt. Ein Problem weniger.",src:"The meeting is over. Verumius survived. Even Frau Müller smiled. In this office, everyone uses du. One problem fewer."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 6: Geburtstagskuchen und Regeln ───
{id:"deu_r14l9",title:"Geburtstagskuchen und Regeln",icon:"🎂",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Geburtstagskuchen und Regeln",desc:"Thomas has a birthday. And he brought his OWN cake! Welcome to the German birthday tradition. Passive and relative clauses in action.",goals:["Discover the German birthday cake tradition","Master passive in both tenses","Use relative clauses to describe colleagues and situations"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"cheerful",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche-cake",trg:"Oh, Thomas hat heute Geburtstag! Schau, er hat einen Kuchen mitgebracht.",src:"Oh, Thomas has his birthday today! Look, he brought a cake."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"confused",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche-cake",trg:"Moment... ER hat den Kuchen mitgebracht? Für seinen EIGENEN Geburtstag?",src:"Wait... HE brought the cake? For his OWN birthday?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"amused",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche-cake",trg:"Natürlich! In Deutschland bringt das Geburtstagskind den Kuchen mit. Der Kuchen wird vom Geburtstagskind selbst gemacht oder gekauft.",src:"Of course! In Germany, the birthday person brings the cake. The cake is made or bought by the birthday person themselves."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Schachtel",src:"the box, the packet",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Smaller than a Kiste. 'Eine Schachtel Pralinen' = a box of chocolates.\nOften used for packaging.",example:"A: Ist das eine Schachtel Pralinen?\nB: Ja, für Thomas. Zum Geburtstag.\nA: Die Schachtel sieht schön aus.\nB: Sie wurde extra verpackt.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that a box of chocolates?\nB: Yes, for Thomas. For his birthday.\nA: The box looks nice.\nB: It was specially wrapped.",funFact:"'Eine Schachtel Pralinen' (a box of chocolates) is a classic German gift. Schachtel is also used as mild slang for an older woman (unflattering), so be careful with context."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kiste",src:"the crate, the chest",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Bigger than a Schachtel. 'Eine Kiste Bier' = a crate of beer.\nYou bring the empty Kiste back for deposit.",example:"A: Kannst du eine Kiste aus dem Lager holen?\nB: Welche Kiste? Es gibt viele dort.\nA: Die große Holzkiste mit den Werkzeugen.\nB: Klar, die Kiste wird sofort geholt.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you get a crate from the storage room?\nB: Which crate? There are many there.\nA: The big wooden crate with the tools.\nB: Sure, the crate will be fetched right away.",funFact:"'Eine Kiste Bier' (a crate of beer) is the standard beer purchase unit in Germany. You bring the empty Kiste back to the store for a deposit (Pfand). A 20-bottle Kiste is the German standard."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kasten",src:"the box, the case, the crate",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Regional: in Bavaria and Austria, 'Kasten' also means wardrobe.\n'Bierkasten' = beer crate.",example:"A: Stell den Kasten bitte in die Ecke.\nB: Welchen Kasten?\nA: Den mit den Getränken.\nB: Ah, der Bierkasten. Wird gemacht.",exampleSrc:"A: Please put the crate in the corner.\nB: Which crate?\nA: The one with the drinks.\nB: Ah, the beer crate. Will be done.",funFact:"In Bavaria and Austria, Kasten also means wardrobe or closet. 'Mein Kasten ist voll' could mean your beer crate is full OR your closet is full, depending on where you are."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Werkzeug",src:"the tool(s)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Werk (work) + Zeug (stuff). Literally 'work-stuff.'\nCollective: all tools together. Individual tools have specific names.",example:"A: Hast du das richtige Werkzeug?\nB: Ja, Hammer, Schraubenzieher und Zange.\nA: Perfekt. Das Regal muss repariert werden.\nB: Das Werkzeug wurde gerade aus dem Keller geholt.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have the right tools?\nB: Yes, hammer, screwdriver, and pliers.\nA: Perfect. The shelf needs to be repaired.\nB: The tools were just fetched from the basement.",funFact:"Das Werkzeug is collective: all your tools together. Zeug literally means 'stuff.' German loves Zeug-compounds: Spielzeug (play-stuff = toys), Fahrzeug (drive-stuff = vehicle), Flugzeug (fly-stuff = airplane)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Hammer",src:"the hammer",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Same word in English and German. From Proto-Germanic.\n'Das ist der Hammer!' = slang for 'That is amazing/unbelievable!'",example:"A: Wo ist der Hammer?\nB: Im Werkzeugkasten. Wozu brauchst du ihn?\nA: Ein Nagel muss in die Wand.\nB: Hier ist der Hammer. Aber klopf nicht zu laut!",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the hammer?\nB: In the toolbox. What do you need it for?\nA: A nail needs to go into the wall.\nB: Here is the hammer. But do not bang too loudly!",funFact:"'Das ist der Hammer!' is German slang for 'That is amazing/unbelievable!' Used both positively and negatively. Hammerhart (hammer-hard) means extremely tough. Hammermäßig means awesome."},
{type:"fb",s:"Hast du das richtige {1}? Hammer, Schraubenzieher und Zange?",a:["Werkzeug"],opts:["Werkzeug","Hammer","Kasten","Kiste"],hint:"The collective neuter noun for all tools together. Werk (work) + Zeug (stuff).",sSrc:"Do you have the right tools? Hammer, screwdriver, and pliers?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Handwerker",src:"the craftsperson, the tradesperson",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Hand + Werk (work) + -er (person). Germany's Handwerker tradition goes back to medieval guilds.",example:"A: Wir brauchen einen Handwerker für das Dach.\nB: Einen Handwerker zu finden ist schwer.\nA: Der letzte Handwerker wurde vor drei Monaten bestellt.\nB: Ja, man muss lange warten.",exampleSrc:"A: We need a tradesperson for the roof.\nB: Finding a tradesperson is difficult.\nA: The last tradesperson was booked three months ago.\nB: Yes, you have to wait a long time.",funFact:"Germany's Handwerker tradition goes back to medieval guilds (Zünfte). Finding a good Handwerker today can take months. The Handwerkskammer (Chamber of Crafts) regulates quality. 'Handwerk hat goldenen Boden' (craftsmanship has a golden foundation)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"kleben",src:"to glue, to stick",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Der Zettel klebt an der Wand' = the note sticks to the wall.\nThose passive-aggressive Kaffeküche notes? They are geklebt everywhere.",example:"A: Wer hat den Zettel an die Wand geklebt?\nB: Keine Ahnung. Er wurde gestern Nacht geklebt.\nA: 'Bitte Küche sauber halten!' steht drauf.\nB: Das wird jede Woche neu geklebt.",exampleSrc:"A: Who stuck the note on the wall?\nB: No idea. It was stuck there last night.\nA: 'Please keep the kitchen clean!' is written on it.\nB: That gets re-stuck every week.",funFact:"Those passive-aggressive Kaffeküche notes are geklebt to every surface in German offices. 'Kleben bleiben' means to stick around. 'Klebstoff' (glue) literally means 'sticky substance.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"stecken",src:"to put in, to insert, to be stuck",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Den Stecker in die Steckdose stecken.'\nStecker and Steckdose come from stecken. German vocabulary is a family tree.",example:"A: Steck bitte den Stecker in die Steckdose.\nB: Welchen Stecker?\nA: Den vom Kopierer.\nB: Ah, der steckt schon drin.",exampleSrc:"A: Please put the plug into the outlet.\nB: Which plug?\nA: The one from the copier.\nB: Ah, it is already plugged in.",funFact:"Stecken, Stecker, Steckdose, Steckbrief (wanted poster, literally 'plug letter'), Stecknadel (pin). German vocabulary is a family tree. One root gives birth to entire word families."},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufheben",src:"to pick up, to keep, to save",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Two meanings: pick up AND keep/save.\n'Heb das auf!' means both 'Pick that up!' and 'Save that!'",example:"A: Heb bitte das Papier vom Boden auf.\nB: Natürlich. Soll ich es aufheben?\nA: Ja, bitte aufheben. Es ist ein wichtiges Dokument.\nB: Okay, das wird sicher aufgehoben.",exampleSrc:"A: Please pick up the paper from the floor.\nB: Of course. Should I keep it?\nA: Yes, please save it. It is an important document.\nB: Okay, it will be safely kept.",funFact:"Aufheben has two meanings: to pick up AND to keep/save. 'Das Gesetz wurde aufgehoben' means the law was abolished (literally 'picked up and removed'). Context decides which meaning applies."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'aufheben'?",opts:["to warm or heat something","to pick up AND to keep/save","to stick a label on","to break apart or malfunction"],ans:"to pick up AND to keep/save",hint:"This verb has two meanings depending on context. Both involve taking something from where it is."}
]},
{id:"deu_r14l9b",title:"Geburtstagskuchen und Regeln (Teil 2)",icon:"🎂",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Geburtstagskuchen und Regeln (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufnehmen",src:"to record, to absorb, to take in",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Auf- (up) + nehmen (to take). 'Ein Gespräch aufnehmen' = to record a conversation.\n'Neue Mitarbeiter aufnehmen' = to take on new employees.",example:"A: Wird die Besprechung aufgenommen?\nB: Ja, alles wird aufgenommen und protokolliert.\nA: Gut. Dann kann ich nachher alles nachhören.\nB: Die Aufnahme wurde gestern getestet.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the meeting being recorded?\nB: Yes, everything is being recorded and documented.\nA: Good. Then I can listen to it later.\nB: The recording was tested yesterday.",funFact:"Aufnehmen means to record, absorb, or take in. 'Etwas in sich aufnehmen' means to absorb something. 'In einen Verein aufgenommen werden' means to be accepted into a club. Multi-talented verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gebrauchen",src:"to use",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ge- + brauchen (to need). 'Gebrauchsanweisung' = instructions for use.\n'Gebraucht' also means secondhand.",example:"A: Wie gebraucht man diesen Kopierer?\nB: Lesen Sie die Gebrauchsanweisung.\nA: Wo ist die?\nB: Sie wurde neben dem Kopierer aufgehängt.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you use this copier?\nB: Read the instructions for use.\nA: Where are they?\nB: They were hung up next to the copier.",funFact:"'Gebraucht' means both used (as in 'I used it') and secondhand. 'Gebrauchtwagen' is a used car. A 'Gebrauchsanweisung' (instructions for use) is on every German product. Reading them is practically a national pastime."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einsetzen",src:"to deploy, to use, to insert",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ein- (in) + setzen (to place). 'Mitarbeiter einsetzen' = to deploy employees.\n'Sich einsetzen für' = to advocate for.",example:"A: Wo wirst du im Betrieb eingesetzt?\nB: In der IT-Abteilung. Ich wurde dort eingesetzt.\nA: Und die neuen Rechner?\nB: Die werden nächste Woche eingesetzt.",exampleSrc:"A: Where will you be deployed in the company?\nB: In the IT department. I was placed there.\nA: And the new computers?\nB: They will be deployed next week.",funFact:"'Sich für etwas einsetzen' (to advocate for something) is a key German phrase. The Betriebsrat setzt sich für die Mitarbeiter ein (advocates for the employees). A word that combines placing and caring."},
{type:"teach",trg:"eckig",src:"angular, square, cornered",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Ecke' (corner). 'Ein eckiger Tisch' = a square table.\n'Ecken und Kanten haben' = to have rough edges (personality).",example:"A: Soll der Tisch rund oder eckig sein?\nB: Eckig. Ein eckiger Tisch passt besser.\nA: Und die Regale?\nB: Auch eckig. Alles hier ist eckig und ordentlich.",exampleSrc:"A: Should the table be round or square?\nB: Square. A square table fits better.\nA: And the shelves?\nB: Also square. Everything here is angular and tidy.",funFact:"'Ecken und Kanten haben' (to have corners and edges) means to have a strong, unpolished personality. Germans appreciate people with Ecken und Kanten over smooth, flawless facades."},
{type:"teach",trg:"senkrecht",src:"vertical, perpendicular",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Senk- (to lower/sink) + recht (right/straight).\nOpposite: waagerecht (horizontal).",example:"A: Hängt das Bild senkrecht?\nB: Nein, es hängt etwas schief.\nA: Soll ich es senkrecht ausrichten?\nB: Ja bitte. Es muss senkrecht hängen.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the picture hanging vertically?\nB: No, it is hanging a bit crooked.\nA: Should I straighten it vertically?\nB: Yes please. It must hang vertically.",funFact:"Senkrecht and waagerecht (vertical and horizontal) are the German pair for crossword puzzles: 'senkrecht' = down, 'waagerecht' = across. Precision in direction is very German."},
{type:"mc",q:"In Deutschland bringt zum Geburtstag im Büro traditionell wer den Kuchen mit?",opts:["Die netten Kollegen","Der Chef oder sein Vertreter","Die zuständige Sekretärin","Das Geburtstagskind selbst"],ans:"Das Geburtstagskind selbst",hint:"German birthday tradition reverses what many cultures expect. The birthday person treats."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Kuchen {1} vom Geburtstagskind mitgebracht.",a:["wird"],opts:["wird","wurde","werden","worden"],hint:"The cake IS brought. Present passive, third person singular.",sSrc:"The cake is brought by the birthday person."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Kaffeküche wurde letzte Woche renoviert.' Was bedeutet das?",opts:["Die Küche wurde letzte Woche erneuert","Die Küche wird gerade renoviert","Die Küche muss noch renoviert werden","Die Küche braucht keine Renovierung"],ans:"Die Küche wurde letzte Woche erneuert",hint:"The original sentence describes something that was done in the recent past. Find the synonym that keeps the same time frame and passive structure."},
{type:"fb",s:"Thomas, {1} heute Geburtstag hat, bringt den Kuchen mit.",a:["der"],opts:["der","den","dem","die"],hint:"Thomas is masculine. He HAS a birthday (subject position). Think masculine subject form.",sSrc:"Thomas, who has his birthday today, brings the cake."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Der Kuchen, {1} von Thomas {2} wurde, schmeckt gut.",blanks:{"1":"der","2":"gebacken"},pool:["der","den","gebacken","backen","wurde","wird"],hint:"Kuchen is masculine, subject of passive relative clause (Nominativ). It WAS baked.",sSrc:"The cake that was baked by Thomas tastes good."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die E-Mail wurde von der Sekretärin gesendet.' Wer hat die E-Mail gesendet?",opts:["Der Direktor","Die Sekretärin","Die E-Mail selbst","Es ist unbekannt"],ans:"Die Sekretärin",hint:"Von + Dativ identifies who performed the action in a passive sentence."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Die Regeln, {1} in der Kaffeküche gelten, {2} ernst genommen.",blanks:{"1":"die","2":"werden"},pool:["die","der","werden","wurde","wird","den"],hint:"Rules (feminine plural, Nominativ in relative clause). They ARE taken seriously (plural passive present).",sSrc:"The rules that apply in the coffee kitchen are taken seriously."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher Satz benutzt Passiv Präteritum IN einem Relativsatz?",opts:["Das Werkzeug, das repariert wurde, funktioniert wieder.","Das Werkzeug, das auf dem alten Tisch liegt, ist sehr alt.","Der erfahrene Handwerker hat das Werkzeug vollständig repariert.","Das schwere Werkzeug wird gerade vom Techniker repariert."],ans:"Das Werkzeug, das repariert wurde, funktioniert wieder.",hint:"Find the sentence where a past passive construction is embedded inside a relative clause, visible by the commas around it."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Schachtel",src:"small box/packet"},{trg:"die Kiste",src:"crate/chest"},{trg:"das Werkzeug",src:"tools"},{trg:"der Hammer",src:"hammer"},{trg:"der Handwerker",src:"craftsperson"}]},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Der Handwerker, {1} gerufen {2}, hat das Regal {3}.",blanks:{"1":"der","2":"wurde","3":"repariert"},pool:["der","den","wurde","wird","repariert","reparieren"],hint:"Masculine Handwerker WHO was called (Nominativ relative + passive). He repaired the shelf.",sSrc:"The craftsperson who was called repaired the shelf."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"bewildered",art:"de-ber-kaffeeküche-cake",trg:"Also. In Deutschland bringt man seinen eigenen Geburtstagskuchen mit. Man macht seinen eigenen Kaffee. Und man nimmt niemals den letzten Keks. Verstanden.",src:"So. In Germany you bring your own birthday cake. You make your own coffee. And you never take the last cookie. Understood."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'aufnehmen'?",opts:["the craftsperson, the tradesperson","to glue, to stick","to record, to absorb, to take in","the hammer"],ans:"to record, to absorb, to take in",hint:"Auf- (up) + nehmen (to receive/grasp). To capture something (audio, photo, info)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to use' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["gebrauchen"],opts:["stecken","der Handwerker","gebrauchen","einsetzen"],hint:"Ge- prefix + brauchen (to need). To make use of something you have.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to use' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'einsetzen'?",opts:["the hammer","to deploy, to use, to insert","the tool(s)","vertical, perpendicular"],ans:"to deploy, to use, to insert",hint:"Ein- (in) + setzen (to set/place). To put something into action or position."},
{type:"fb",s:"Soll der Tisch rund oder {1} sein?",a:["eckig"],opts:["einsetzen","der Kasten","die Schachtel","eckig"],hint:"From Ecke (corner). The -ig suffix makes it an adjective: having corners.",sSrc:"Should the table be round or square?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'senkrecht'?",opts:["the box, the packet","to put in, to insert, to be stuck","vertical, perpendicular","to deploy, to use, to insert"],ans:"vertical, perpendicular",hint:"Senken (to lower/sink) + recht (right/straight). A plumb line goes straight down."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 7: Alles zusammen ───
{id:"deu_r14l10",title:"Alles zusammen",icon:"🧪",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Alles zusammen",desc:"Test everything you have learned about passive and relative clauses. Prove you can describe workplace events, technology, and people in German.",goals:["Test passive Präsens and Präteritum in combination","Master relative clauses in all three cases","Combine all three constructions in office contexts"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"reflective",art:"de-ber-office-afternoon",trg:"Es ist Nachmittag. Verumius kennt jetzt die Kaffeküche-Regeln, die Du/Sie-Grenze und die Geburtstagskuchen-Tradition. Aber der Arbeitstag ist noch nicht vorbei.",src:"It is afternoon. Verumius now knows the coffee kitchen rules, the Du/Sie boundary, and the birthday cake tradition. But the workday is not over yet."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Fernseher",src:"the television set",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Fern (far) + Seher (viewer). Literally 'far-viewer.'\nUsually means the TV set, not the activity.",example:"A: Haben wir einen Fernseher im Konferenzraum?\nB: Ja, ein großer Fernseher hängt an der Wand.\nA: Der Fernseher wurde letzte Woche installiert.\nB: Perfekt für Präsentationen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do we have a television in the conference room?\nB: Yes, a large TV hangs on the wall.\nA: The TV was installed last week.\nB: Perfect for presentations.",funFact:"Fern (far) + Seher (viewer) creates 'far-viewer.' The German word describes exactly what TV does. 'Glotze' (starer) is the slang word for TV, from 'glotzen' (to stare)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Fernsehen",src:"the television (medium)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Fern (far) + sehen (to see). The medium, not the device.\n'Fernsehen gucken' = to watch TV.",example:"A: Wie oft schaust du Fernsehen?\nB: Jeden Abend. Nachrichten und Serien.\nA: Im Fernsehen wird viel über Politik berichtet.\nB: Ja, besonders in den Nachrichten.",exampleSrc:"A: How often do you watch television?\nB: Every evening. News and series.\nA: On television a lot is reported about politics.\nB: Yes, especially in the news.",funFact:"Fernsehen (the medium) versus Fernseher (the device). 'Im Fernsehen' means on TV. Germans love their Tatort (crime scene) on Sunday evenings. It is practically a national ritual."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fernbedienung",src:"the remote control",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Fern (far) + Bedienung (operation). Literally 'far-operation.'\nA perfect German compound that describes exactly what it does.",example:"A: Wo ist die Fernbedienung?\nB: Unter dem Kissen auf der Couch.\nA: Da liegt sie immer! Warum wird sie nie zurückgelegt?\nB: Das ist eines der großen Büro-Mysterien.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the remote control?\nB: Under the cushion on the couch.\nA: It is always there! Why is it never put back?\nB: That is one of the great office mysteries.",funFact:"Fernbedienung is one of those perfect German compounds: Fern (far) + Bedienung (operation/service). It describes exactly what the thing does. English 'remote control' does the same, but the German version is one elegant word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Lautsprecher",src:"the loudspeaker, the speaker",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Laut (loud) + Sprecher (speaker). Same compound logic as English.\nUsed for speakers on computers, phones, PA systems.",example:"A: Der Lautsprecher funktioniert nicht.\nB: Welcher Lautsprecher? Der am Rechner?\nA: Ja. Es wird kein Ton wiedergegeben.\nB: Das Kabel wurde wahrscheinlich nicht richtig angeschlossen.",exampleSrc:"A: The speaker is not working.\nB: Which speaker? The one on the computer?\nA: Yes. No sound is being played.\nB: The cable was probably not connected properly.",funFact:"Laut (loud) + Sprecher (speaker) mirrors English for once. German and English share this compound logic because both descend from Proto-Germanic. Not all borrowing goes one direction."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wo ist die {1}? Ich muss den Kanal wechseln.",a:["Fernbedienung"],opts:["Fernbedienung","Festplatte","Tastatur","Kassette"],hint:"Fern (far) + Bedienung (operation). The handheld device for controlling a TV.",sSrc:"Where is the remote control? I need to change the channel."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Sender",src:"the transmitter, the TV/radio station",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'senden' (to send). A transmitter or broadcasting station.\nARD and ZDF are Germany's biggest Sender.",example:"A: Auf welchem Sender läuft das?\nB: Auf dem Ersten. Das ist der größte Sender.\nA: Und der Sender wird staatlich finanziert?\nB: Ja, durch den Rundfunkbeitrag. Jeder zahlt.",exampleSrc:"A: On which channel is that on?\nB: On Das Erste. That is the biggest station.\nA: And the station is state-funded?\nB: Yes, through the broadcasting fee. Everyone pays.",funFact:"ARD and ZDF are Germany's public broadcasters, funded by the Rundfunkbeitrag (broadcasting fee) of 18.36 euros per month per household. Every household must pay, whether they watch TV or not."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kanal",src:"the channel, the canal",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Auf welchem Kanal?' = On which channel?\nFrom Latin 'canalis.' Also a waterway.",example:"A: Auf welchem Kanal kommt die Sendung?\nB: Kanal drei. Um zwanzig Uhr.\nA: Und die Wiederholung?\nB: Die wird auf einem anderen Kanal gesendet.",exampleSrc:"A: On which channel is the show on?\nB: Channel three. At eight PM.\nA: And the rerun?\nB: It will be broadcast on a different channel.",funFact:"Germany has dozens of TV Kanäle. The public ones (ARD, ZDF) coexist with private ones (RTL, ProSieben). The 'Kanalwechsel' (channel switching) between public and private is a daily German ritual."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kassette",src:"the cassette",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From French. Audio and video cassettes.\nAlmost extinct but still understood by all Germans.",example:"A: Was ist das? Eine Kassette?\nB: Ja, eine alte Videokassette. Die wurde im Keller gefunden.\nA: Haben wir noch einen Kassettenrekorder?\nB: Nein, der wurde vor Jahren weggeworfen.",exampleSrc:"A: What is that? A cassette?\nB: Yes, an old video cassette. It was found in the basement.\nA: Do we still have a cassette recorder?\nB: No, it was thrown away years ago.",funFact:"The Kassette is almost extinct in Germany, replaced by digital media. But 'Hörspielkassetten' (audio play cassettes) were a huge part of German childhood. The detective series 'Die drei Fragezeichen' sold millions of Kassetten."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Laufwerk",src:"the drive (computer)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Lauf (run) + Werk (work). A disc drive or storage drive.\n'CD-Laufwerk,' 'DVD-Laufwerk.' Being phased out.",example:"A: Mein Rechner hat kein CD-Laufwerk mehr.\nB: Die neuen Rechner werden ohne Laufwerk gebaut.\nA: Wie installiere ich dann Software?\nB: Alles wird online heruntergeladen.",exampleSrc:"A: My computer does not have a CD drive anymore.\nB: The new computers are built without drives.\nA: How do I install software then?\nB: Everything is downloaded online.",funFact:"Laufwerk (run-work) refers to any disk drive. CD-Laufwerke and DVD-Laufwerke are vanishing from modern computers. The word persists in IT jargon though: Netzlaufwerk (network drive) is still common."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Fernseher",src:"TV set"},{trg:"das Fernsehen",src:"television (medium)"},{trg:"die Fernbedienung",src:"remote control"},{trg:"der Lautsprecher",src:"speaker"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist der Unterschied zwischen 'der Sender' und 'der Kanal'?",opts:["Es gibt zwischen beiden keinen Unterschied","Sender ist die Station, Kanal ist die Nummer","Sender ist nur für Radio, Kanal ist nur für Fernsehen","Kanal ist das österreichische Wort für Sender"],ans:"Sender ist die Station, Kanal ist die Nummer",hint:"One refers to the broadcasting organization, the other to the numbered frequency you tune to."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die alte Videokassette {1} im Keller gefunden.",a:["wurde"],opts:["wurde","wird","werden","worden"],hint:"The cassette WAS found. Past passive, singular.",sSrc:"The old video cassette was found in the basement."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wo ist die {1}? Ich kann den Fernseher nicht einschalten.",a:["Fernbedienung"],opts:["Fernbedienung","Kassette","Lautsprecher","Kanal"],hint:"The handheld device used to control a TV from a distance.",sSrc:"Where is the remote control? I cannot turn on the television."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Fernseher",src:"the television set"},{trg:"die Fernbedienung",src:"the remote control"},{trg:"der Lautsprecher",src:"the loudspeaker"},{trg:"der Kanal",src:"the channel"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Sender'?",opts:["the television remote control","the old audio cassette","the frequency channel","the TV or radio station"],ans:"the TV or radio station",hint:"Think of who sends out the broadcast signal. Also means transmitter."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich suche die {1} für den Fernseher.",a:["Fernbedienung"],opts:["Fernbedienung","Kassette","Lautsprecher","Laufwerk"],hint:"You use this device to change channels without getting up.",sSrc:"I am looking for the remote control for the television."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist der Unterschied zwischen 'der Fernseher' und 'das Fernsehen'?",opts:["Es gibt zwischen beiden Begriffen gar keinen Unterschied","Fernsehen ist nur die österreichische Variante davon","Fernseher ist das Gerät, Fernsehen ist das Medium","Fernseher ist immer die formellere Version"],ans:"Fernseher ist das Gerät, Fernsehen ist das Medium",hint:"One word is the physical object in your living room. The other describes the entire system of broadcasting and reception."}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Computer und Software ───
{id:"deu_r14l11",title:"Computer und Software",icon:"💻",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Computer und Software",desc:"Uploading, downloading, installing, deleting, charging, and breaking things: the essential German verbs of digital life in the modern office.",goals:["Learn computer and software action verbs","Describe technical processes using passive voice","Master compound tech vocabulary"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"abonnieren",src:"to subscribe",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From French 'abonner.' Regular -ieren verb.\n'Einen Kanal abonnieren' = to subscribe to a channel.",example:"A: Hast du den Newsletter abonniert?\nB: Ja, er wurde letzte Woche abonniert.\nA: Und die Zeitung?\nB: Die wird ab nächstem Monat abonniert.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you subscribe to the newsletter?\nB: Yes, it was subscribed to last week.\nA: And the newspaper?\nB: It will be subscribed to starting next month.",funFact:"Germans love their Abos (abbreviation of Abonnement). Streaming, gym, magazine, newspaper: everything runs on Abonnements. 'Abo-Falle' (subscription trap) is the German term for sneaky auto-renewing subscriptions."},
{type:"teach",trg:"hochladen",src:"to upload",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Hoch (up) + laden (to load). Separable verb.\nOpposite: herunterladen (to download).",example:"A: Kannst du die Datei hochladen?\nB: Ja, sie wird gerade hochgeladen.\nA: Wie lange dauert das?\nB: Nur eine Minute. Die Datei wurde schon komprimiert.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you upload the file?\nB: Yes, it is being uploaded right now.\nA: How long does it take?\nB: Only a minute. The file was already compressed.",funFact:"Hochladen (upload) and herunterladen (download) are literal translations: hoch (up) + laden (load) and herunter (down) + laden (load). German tech vocabulary loves to create transparent compounds."},
{type:"teach",trg:"herunterfahren",src:"to shut down (a computer)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Herunter- (down) + fahren (to drive). Proper shutdown.\nDifferent from ausschalten (just turning off).",example:"A: Bitte fahren Sie den Computer herunter.\nB: Wird sofort heruntergefahren.\nA: Nicht einfach ausschalten!\nB: Nein, nein. Er wird ordentlich heruntergefahren.",exampleSrc:"A: Please shut down the computer.\nB: It will be shut down right away.\nA: Do not just turn it off!\nB: No, no. It will be properly shut down.",funFact:"Germans distinguish between herunterfahren (proper shutdown process) and ausschalten (just turning off). 'Fahr den Rechner runter!' is the proper way. Just pressing the power button is considered barbarisch."},
{type:"teach",trg:"installieren",src:"to install",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'installare.' Regular -ieren verb.\n'Software installieren' = universal tech language.",example:"A: Wurde die neue Software schon installiert?\nB: Ja, sie wurde gestern installiert.\nA: Und funktioniert sie?\nB: Ja, alles wird gerade getestet.",exampleSrc:"A: Has the new software been installed yet?\nB: Yes, it was installed yesterday.\nA: And does it work?\nB: Yes, everything is being tested right now.",funFact:"German IT vocabulary is heavily English-influenced but grammar stays German. Installieren follows German conjugation: ich installiere, du installierst, es wurde installiert. The -ieren ending always means regular conjugation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"löschen",src:"to delete, to extinguish",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Eine Datei löschen' = delete a file.\n'Ein Feuer löschen' = extinguish a fire. Same verb for both.",example:"A: Soll ich die alten Dateien löschen?\nB: Ja, die können gelöscht werden.\nA: Alle?\nB: Nein, nur die, die älter als ein Jahr sind.",exampleSrc:"A: Should I delete the old files?\nB: Yes, they can be deleted.\nA: All of them?\nB: No, only those that are older than one year.",funFact:"Löschen means both delete and extinguish. 'Feuerlöscher' (fire extinguisher) and 'Datei löschen' (delete file) use the same verb. In both cases, something is completely removed."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Soll ich die alten Dateien löschen?' Was bedeutet löschen?",opts:["to delete/extinguish","to save","to upload","to install"],ans:"to delete/extinguish",hint:"Used for both deleting files and putting out fires. The same verb for both."},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufladen",src:"to charge, to load up",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Auf- (up) + laden (to load). 'Das Handy aufladen' = to charge the phone.\nAlso: 'eine Karte aufladen' = to top up a card.",example:"A: Mein Laptop muss aufgeladen werden.\nB: Hier ist eine freie Steckdose.\nA: Danke. Wie lange wird der Laptop aufgeladen?\nB: Eine Stunde reicht meistens.",exampleSrc:"A: My laptop needs to be charged.\nB: Here is a free outlet.\nA: Thanks. How long will the laptop be charged?\nB: One hour is usually enough.",funFact:"Aufladen means to charge (a device) or to load up (a truck). 'Emotional aufgeladen' means emotionally charged. The word works for batteries, vehicles, and feelings."},
{type:"teach",trg:"kaputtgehen",src:"to break down, to stop working",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Kaputt (broken) + gehen (to go). Separable verb.\nKaputt comes from French 'capot' (a losing hand in cards).",example:"A: Der Drucker ist kaputtgegangen.\nB: Schon wieder? Er geht ständig kaputt.\nA: Wann wird er repariert?\nB: Der Handwerker wurde schon gerufen.",exampleSrc:"A: The printer has broken down.\nB: Again? It breaks down constantly.\nA: When will it be repaired?\nB: The tradesperson has already been called.",funFact:"Kaputt comes from French 'capot' (a losing hand in cards). When something is kaputt, it is game over. 'Kaputtlachen' means to laugh so hard you break. 'Kaputt sein' also means to be exhausted."},
{type:"teach",trg:"kaputtmachen",src:"to break, to destroy",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Active version of kaputtgehen. 'Wer hat das kaputtgemacht?'\nKaputtgehen = it breaks itself. Kaputtmachen = someone breaks it.",example:"A: Wer hat den Kopierer kaputtgemacht?\nB: Niemand weiß es.\nA: Er wurde wahrscheinlich falsch bedient.\nB: Ja, die Bedienungsanleitung wird nie gelesen.",exampleSrc:"A: Who broke the copier?\nB: Nobody knows.\nA: It was probably operated incorrectly.\nB: Yes, the user manual is never read.",funFact:"Kaputtgehen = it breaks by itself. Kaputtmachen = someone breaks it. The distinction matters in German offices where blame is a serious matter. 'Das war schon kaputt!' (That was already broken!) is the universal defense."},
{type:"teach",trg:"virtuell",src:"virtual",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'virtualis.' 'Virtuelles Meeting' = virtual meeting.\nBecame everyday vocabulary after 2020.",example:"A: Die Konferenz findet virtuell statt.\nB: Wieder ein virtuelles Meeting?\nA: Ja, alle Teilnehmer werden virtuell zugeschaltet.\nB: Ich bevorzuge persönliche Besprechungen.",exampleSrc:"A: The conference is taking place virtually.\nB: Another virtual meeting?\nA: Yes, all participants will be connected virtually.\nB: I prefer in-person meetings.",funFact:"'Virtuelles Meeting' became everyday vocabulary in Germany after 2020. Before that, the word virtuell was mainly used for 'virtuelle Realität' (virtual reality). Now every German office worker knows 'virtuelle Besprechung.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Software wird heute installiert.' Was passiert?",opts:["Die Software wird heute eingerichtet","Die Software wurde gestern installiert","Die Software wird morgen installiert","Die Software muss noch bestellt werden"],ans:"Die Software wird heute eingerichtet",hint:"The original sentence says it happens today. Find the option that paraphrases it with the same time reference and passive meaning."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der alte Fernseher {1} letzte Woche ersetzt.",a:["wurde"],opts:["wurde","wird","werden","worden"],hint:"The old TV WAS replaced last week. Past passive, singular.",sSrc:"The old television was replaced last week."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ein Lautsprecher, ___ nicht funktioniert, muss repariert werden.' Welches Pronomen?",opts:["das (falsch)","der","dem","den"],ans:"der",hint:"Lautsprecher is masculine. It does NOT function (subject position). Think masculine subject form."},
{type:"fb",s:"Meine Lampe, {1} ich gestern gekauft habe, ist kaputt.",a:["die"],opts:["die","der","den","dem"],hint:"Lampe is feminine. I bought IT (direct object = accusative). Feminine accusative form is needed.",sSrc:"My lamp that I bought yesterday is broken."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Der Rechner, der gestern repariert wurde, funktioniert wieder.' Was ist passiert?",opts:["Er wird morgen repariert","Er wird gerade repariert","Er wurde gestern repariert und geht wieder","Er ist gestern kaputtgegangen"],ans:"Er wurde gestern repariert und geht wieder",hint:"Look for the option that uses past passive and confirms the device is now back in working order."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Die Datei {1} auf den Server {2}.",blanks:{"1":"wird","2":"hochgeladen"},pool:["wird","wurde","hochgeladen","hochladen","geladen","werden"],hint:"The action is happening right now, not in the past. Use the present tense passive auxiliary, then place the past participle at the end.",sSrc:"The file is being uploaded to the server."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Kollege, {1} ich geholfen habe, ist sehr dankbar.",a:["dem"],opts:["dem","den","der","die"],hint:"Kollege is masculine. Helfen governs dative. I helped TO HIM. Think masculine dative.",sSrc:"The colleague whom I helped is very grateful."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Festplatte wurde vom Techniker ausgetauscht.' Wer hat die Festplatte ersetzt?",opts:["Der Leiter","Die Festplatte selbst","Unbekannt","Der Techniker"],ans:"Der Techniker",hint:"Vom (von + dem) Dativ tells you who performed the passive action."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Das Programm, {1} gestern {2} wurde, funktioniert nicht.",blanks:{"1":"das","2":"installiert"},pool:["das","der","installiert","installieren","wurde","wird"],hint:"Programm is neuter, subject in relative clause (Nominativ). It WAS installed (Passiv Präteritum).",sSrc:"The program that was installed yesterday does not work."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Heute {1} die Software aktualisiert. Gestern {2} der Drucker repariert.",blanks:{"1":"wird","2":"wurde"},pool:["wird","wurde","werden","wurden"],hint:"The first sentence refers to today, the second to yesterday. Choose the passive auxiliary that matches each time frame.",sSrc:"Today the software is being updated. Yesterday the printer was repaired."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher Satz kombiniert Relativsatz + Passiv Präteritum + Dativ korrekt?",opts:["Der Kollege, die geholfen wurde, ist zufrieden.","Der Kollege, der geholfen wurde, ist zufrieden.","Der Kollege, dem geholfen wurde, ist jetzt zufrieden.","Der Kollege, den geholfen wurde, ist zufrieden."],ans:"Der Kollege, dem geholfen wurde, ist jetzt zufrieden.",hint:"Helfen governs dative. The colleague TO WHOM help was given. Think masculine dative form."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"hochladen",src:"to upload"},{trg:"herunterfahren",src:"to shut down"},{trg:"löschen",src:"to delete"},{trg:"installieren",src:"to install"},{trg:"kaputtgehen",src:"to break down"}]},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Die Dateien, {1} gelöscht {2}, {3} wichtig.",blanks:{"1":"die","2":"wurden","3":"waren"},pool:["die","der","wurden","wurde","waren","war"],hint:"Files (feminine plural, Nominativ). They WERE deleted (plural passive past). They WERE important.",sSrc:"The files that were deleted were important."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Der Sender, ___ wir gestern empfangen haben, wurde abgeschaltet.' Welches Pronomen und warum?",opts:["die (falsch)","den","dem","der"],ans:"den",hint:"Sender is masculine. We received IT (direct object in the relative clause = accusative). Think masculine accusative."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"tired-but-proud",art:"de-ber-office-afternoon",trg:"Mein Kopf ist voll mit Passiv und Relativsätzen. Aber ich habe den Kopierer bedient, ohne ihn kaputtzumachen. Das zählt als Erfolg.",src:"My head is full of passive and relative clauses. But I operated the copier without breaking it. That counts as a success."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich möchte die Zeitschrift ___. Dann bekomme ich sie jeden Monat.",opts:["abonnieren","aufladen","installieren","löschen"],ans:"abonnieren",hint:"A verb meaning to sign up for regular delivery of a publication or service."},
{type:"fb",s:"Mein Handy ist leer. Ich muss es {1}.",a:"aufladen",opts:["aufladen","abonnieren","kaputtmachen","hochladen"],hint:"A separable verb meaning to charge a device or refill a card.",sSrc:"My phone is empty. I need to charge it."},
{type:"mc",q:"Pass auf, du wirst den Drucker noch ___!",opts:["kaputtmachen","aufladen","abonnieren","herausfinden"],ans:"kaputtmachen",hint:"A separable verb meaning to break or destroy something through careless use."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Meeting findet {1} statt, nicht im Büro.",a:"virtuell",opts:["virtuell","digital","technisch","elektronisch"],hint:"This adjective describes something happening online, not in a physical space.",sSrc:"The meeting takes place virtually, not in the office."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 8: Rund ums Gebäude ───
{id:"deu_r14l12",title:"Rund ums Gebäude",icon:"🏢",xp:10,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Rund ums Gebäude",desc:"It is 16:58. Computers are being shut down. Feierabend is sacred. As Verumius walks out through the building, learn the vocabulary of buildings, rooms, and the things inside them, including Austrian variants tested on the Goethe exam.",goals:["Learn building and room vocabulary (Treppenhaus, Dach, Korridor)","Discover Austrian German variants (Lift, Stiege, Fauteuil, Kuvert)","Master household objects and small items (Nadel, Nagel, Vase)"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"observant",art:"de-ber-office-evening",trg:"Es ist 16:58 Uhr. Etwas Seltsames passiert. Überall im Büro werden Computer heruntergefahren. Jacken werden angezogen. Taschen werden gepackt.",src:"It is 4:58 PM. Something strange is happening. All around the office, computers are being shut down. Jackets are being put on. Bags are being packed."},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"matter-of-fact",art:"de-ber-office-evening",trg:"Feierabend! Kommst du? Um 17 Uhr ist Schluss. Die Arbeit, die nicht erledigt wurde, wird morgen gemacht.",src:"End of work! Are you coming? At 5 PM it is over. The work that was not finished will be done tomorrow."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"surprised",art:"de-ber-office-evening",trg:"Aber... ich bin noch nicht fertig mit dem Bericht, der geschrieben werden muss!",src:"But... I am not yet finished with the report that needs to be written!"},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"wise",art:"de-ber-office-exit",trg:"Der Bericht wird morgen geschrieben. Feierabend ist heilig. Die Überstunden, die hier gemacht werden, werden genau gezählt.",src:"The report will be written tomorrow. Feierabend is sacred. The overtime that is worked here is counted precisely."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Treppenhaus",src:"the stairwell, the staircase",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Treppe (stairs) + Haus (house). The architectural soul of German buildings.\nMany Treppenhäuser have strict Hausordnung rules.",example:"A: Nehmen wir den Aufzug oder das Treppenhaus?\nB: Das Treppenhaus. Nur zwei Etagen.\nA: Gut. Das Treppenhaus wurde gerade geputzt.\nB: Der Hausmeister reinigt es jeden Montag.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we take the elevator or the stairwell?\nB: The stairwell. Only two floors.\nA: Good. The stairwell was just cleaned.\nB: The caretaker cleans it every Monday.",funFact:"The Treppenhaus is the architectural soul of German apartment buildings. Many have strict Hausordnung rules about noise and cleaning. 'Kehrwoche' (sweeping week) is a rotating schedule where residents clean the Treppenhaus."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Dach",src:"the roof",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Same root as English 'thatch.' 'Unter einem Dach' = under one roof.\n'Dachgeschoss' (roof floor) = attic apartment.",example:"A: Das Dach des Bürogebäudes wurde letztes Jahr renoviert.\nB: War es kaputt?\nA: Ja, es gab ein Loch im Dach.\nB: Das Loch wurde vom Handwerker repariert.",exampleSrc:"A: The roof of the office building was renovated last year.\nB: Was it broken?\nA: Yes, there was a hole in the roof.\nB: The hole was repaired by the tradesperson.",funFact:"'Unter einem Dach' (under one roof) means living or working together. 'Dachgeschoss' (roof floor) is the attic apartment, very popular in Berlin. 'Ein Dach über dem Kopf haben' means to have shelter."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Korridor",src:"the corridor",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From French/Latin. More formal than Flur or Gang.\nUsed in official buildings and large office complexes.",example:"A: Der Korridor zum Konferenzraum ist lang.\nB: Ja, das Gebäude ist groß.\nA: Der Korridor wurde gerade renoviert.\nB: Deshalb sieht er so neu aus.",exampleSrc:"A: The corridor to the conference room is long.\nB: Yes, the building is large.\nA: The corridor was just renovated.\nB: That is why it looks so new.",funFact:"Korridor is more formal than Flur or Gang. In hospitals, government buildings, and large offices, you walk through Korridore. In apartments and small offices, you walk through Flure."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bau",src:"the construction, the building",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Der Bau' = construction or a building under construction.\nPlural: die Bauten (buildings) or die Baue (animal burrows).",example:"A: Neben unserem Büro ist ein Bau.\nB: Ja, da wird ein neues Gebäude gebaut.\nA: Der Bau wurde letztes Jahr begonnen.\nB: Er soll nächstes Jahr fertig sein.",exampleSrc:"A: Next to our office is a construction site.\nB: Yes, a new building is being built there.\nA: The construction was started last year.\nB: It should be finished next year.",funFact:"Bau has many meanings: construction, building, structure, den (animal). 'Baufirma' (construction company), 'Bauarbeiter' (construction worker), 'Baustelle' (construction site). Germany is always in a state of Bau."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kabine",src:"the cabin, the booth",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Umkleidekabine (changing room), Telefonkabine (phone booth).\nFrom French 'cabine.'",example:"A: Wo ist die Umkleidekabine?\nB: Am Ende des Korridors.\nA: Gibt es auch eine Duschkabine?\nB: Ja, die wurde letztes Jahr eingebaut.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the changing room?\nB: At the end of the corridor.\nA: Is there also a shower cabin?\nB: Yes, it was installed last year.",funFact:"Kabine appears in many compounds: Umkleidekabine (changing room), Telefonkabine (phone booth), Flugzeugkabine (airplane cabin), Duschkabine (shower stall). The phone Kabine is nearly extinct."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Schaufenster",src:"the shop window, the display window",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Schau (look/show) + Fenster (window). Literally 'look-window.'\n'Schaufensterbummel' = window shopping.",example:"A: Hast du das Schaufenster gesehen?\nB: Ja, es wurde neu dekoriert.\nA: Die Produkte im Schaufenster sehen toll aus.\nB: Schaufensterbummel machen wir am Wochenende.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you see the display window?\nB: Yes, it was newly decorated.\nA: The products in the window look great.\nB: We will go window shopping on the weekend.",funFact:"'Schaufensterbummel' (window shopping stroll) is a beloved German pastime. 'Schaufensterpuppe' (display window doll) is a mannequin. The Schaufenster is the boundary between looking and buying."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'das Treppenhaus'?",opts:["the narrow roof","the stairwell","the long corridor","the main elevator"],ans:"the stairwell",hint:"Treppe means stairs, Haus means house. Together they form a building feature."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das {1} des Bürogebäudes wurde letztes Jahr renoviert.",a:["Dach"],opts:["Dach","Treppenhaus","Korridor","Bau"],hint:"The building's top covering was renovated last year.",sSrc:"The roof of the office building was renovated last year."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Lift",src:"the elevator, the lift",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From English 'lift.' More common in Austria and Switzerland.\nIn Germany, 'Aufzug' or 'Fahrstuhl' are more standard.",example:"A: Nehmen wir den Lift oder die Treppe?\nB: Den Lift. Meine Beine sind müde.\nA: Der Lift wurde gestern repariert.\nB: Gut, dann funktioniert er wieder.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we take the elevator or the stairs?\nB: The elevator. My legs are tired.\nA: The elevator was repaired yesterday.\nB: Good, then it works again.",funFact:"Lift is more common in Austria and Switzerland. Germany prefers Aufzug or Fahrstuhl (drive-chair). All three mean elevator. Regional vocabulary differences within German-speaking countries are enormous."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Stiege",src:"the staircase (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Austrian and southern German for 'Treppe' (stairs).\nStiegenhaus = Treppenhaus = stairwell.",example:"A: Nehmen wir die Stiege oder den Lift?\nB: Die Stiege. Ist gesünder.\nA: In Deutschland sagt man Treppe.\nB: Ja, Stiege ist österreichisch.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we take the stairs or the elevator?\nB: The stairs. It is healthier.\nA: In Germany they say Treppe.\nB: Yes, Stiege is Austrian.",funFact:"Stiege is the Austrian word for stairs (Treppe). Stiegenhaus = Treppenhaus = stairwell. Austrian German has hundreds of unique words. Learning them is part of mastering German for the whole DACH region."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Stiegenhaus",src:"the stairwell (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Austrian variant of Treppenhaus. Stiege + Haus.\nUsed throughout Austria and parts of southern Germany.",example:"A: Das Stiegenhaus in diesem Gebäude ist schön.\nB: Ja, es wurde im Jugendstil gebaut.\nA: In Deutschland sagt man Treppenhaus.\nB: Richtig. Stiegenhaus ist typisch österreichisch.",exampleSrc:"A: The stairwell in this building is beautiful.\nB: Yes, it was built in Art Nouveau style.\nA: In Germany they say Treppenhaus.\nB: Right. Stiegenhaus is typically Austrian.",funFact:"The DACH region (Deutschland, Austria, Swiss) shares a language but has distinct vocabulary. Stiegenhaus (AT), Treppenhaus (DE), Stiegenhaus (CH-partly). The Goethe exam tests all variants."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Fauteuil",src:"the armchair (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From French 'fauteuil.' Used in Austria and Switzerland.\nIn Germany, people say 'Sessel' instead.",example:"A: Was für ein schöner Fauteuil!\nB: Danke, der ist aus Wien.\nA: In Deutschland sagt man Sessel.\nB: Ja, Fauteuil ist österreichisch.",exampleSrc:"A: What a beautiful armchair!\nB: Thanks, it is from Vienna.\nA: In Germany they say Sessel.\nB: Yes, Fauteuil is Austrian.",funFact:"Fauteuil is the Austrian and Swiss word for a comfortable armchair. It comes directly from French. German, Austrian, and Swiss German have many such vocabulary differences, making the language wonderfully diverse."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Kuvert",src:"the envelope",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From French 'couvert.' More common in Austria and Switzerland.\nIn Germany, 'Umschlag' or 'Briefumschlag' is more common.",example:"A: Hast du ein Kuvert für diesen Brief?\nB: Ja, hier. Das Kuvert wurde schon beschriftet.\nA: In Deutschland sagt man Umschlag.\nB: Stimmt. Kuvert ist eher österreichisch.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have an envelope for this letter?\nB: Yes, here. The envelope was already labeled.\nA: In Germany they say Umschlag.\nB: True. Kuvert is more Austrian.",funFact:"Kuvert is the Austrian/Swiss word for envelope. In Germany, Briefumschlag (letter envelope) is standard. These DACH vocabulary differences appear on the Goethe exam, so learning all variants matters."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Eck",src:"the corner",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Short for 'die Ecke.' More common in southern German.\n'Am Eck' = at the corner.",example:"A: Stell den Kasten bitte in das Eck.\nB: Welches Eck?\nA: Das Eck neben dem Regal.\nB: Okay, der Kasten wird ins Eck gestellt.",exampleSrc:"A: Please put the crate in the corner.\nB: Which corner?\nA: The corner next to the shelf.\nB: Okay, the crate will be put in the corner.",funFact:"Eck is the southern German/Austrian variant of Ecke (corner). 'Dreieck' (triangle) = three corners. 'Viereck' (rectangle/square) = four corners. German geometry is built on Ecken."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Lift",src:"elevator (Austrian)"},{trg:"die Stiege",src:"staircase (Austrian)"},{trg:"der Fauteuil",src:"armchair (Austrian)"},{trg:"das Kuvert",src:"envelope (Austrian)"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"In Austria, what word is used for 'Treppenhaus'?",opts:["der Korridor","das Eck","der Aufzug","das Stiegenhaus"],ans:"das Stiegenhaus",hint:"It combines the Austrian word for stairs with Haus."}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Zu Hause und im Büro ───
{id:"deu_r14l13",title:"Zu Hause und im Büro",icon:"🏠",xp:10,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Zu Hause und im Büro",desc:"Couches, ovens, alarm clocks, stains, needles, and nails: the small objects that fill German homes and offices. Master everyday vocabulary for describing spaces and things.",goals:["Learn household object vocabulary","Describe items and their locations","Use passive voice with everyday objects"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Couch",src:"the couch, the sofa",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Borrowed from English/French. Die Couch is feminine.\nAfter Feierabend, the Couch is the destination.",example:"A: Nach dem Feierabend liege ich auf der Couch.\nB: Ich auch. Die Couch ist mein bester Freund.\nA: Unsere Couch wurde letzten Monat neu gekauft.\nB: Eine gute Investition.",exampleSrc:"A: After work I lie on the couch.\nB: Me too. The couch is my best friend.\nA: Our couch was bought new last month.\nB: A good investment.",funFact:"After Feierabend, die Couch is the destination for many Germans. 'Couchpotato' has been adopted into German. The German equivalent is 'Couchkartoffel' (couch potato), a literal translation that sounds even funnier."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vase",src:"the vase",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Pronounced 'VAH-zeh' in German, not like English.\nEvery German office has at least one Vase with flowers.",example:"A: Wo kommt diese Vase hin?\nB: Auf den Tisch in der Kaffeküche.\nA: Die Vase wurde von der Leiterin mitgebracht.\nB: Schön, mit frischen Blumen.",exampleSrc:"A: Where does this vase go?\nB: On the table in the coffee kitchen.\nA: The vase was brought by the manager.\nB: Nice, with fresh flowers.",funFact:"Germans pronounce Vase as 'VAH-zeh,' very different from the English 'vayz.' Flowers on the office table are common in German workplaces. A Blumenvase (flower vase) brings life to the Büroalltag (office routine)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Ofen",src:"the oven, the stove, the heater",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Backofen' = baking oven. 'Kachelofen' = tiled stove.\n'Jetzt ist der Ofen aus!' = Now the show is over! (idiom).",example:"A: Gibt es einen Ofen in der Kaffeküche?\nB: Ja, einen kleinen Backofen. Für Kuchen.\nA: Der wurde von Thomas benutzt.\nB: Natürlich. Er hat seinen Geburtstagskuchen gebacken.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there an oven in the coffee kitchen?\nB: Yes, a small baking oven. For cakes.\nA: It was used by Thomas.\nB: Of course. He baked his birthday cake.",funFact:"'Jetzt ist der Ofen aus!' (now the oven is off) means the game is over, no more chances. A Kachelofen (tiled stove) is a traditional German heating stove, beautifully decorated with ceramic tiles."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Wecker",src:"the alarm clock",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'wecken' (to wake). The enemy of every Monday morning.\n'Der Wecker klingelt um sechs' is the most dreaded German sentence.",example:"A: Um wie viel Uhr klingelt dein Wecker?\nB: Um sechs. Jeden Morgen.\nA: Das ist früh. Mein Wecker wird auf sieben gestellt.\nB: Du hast es gut. Um sechs wird bei mir aufgestanden.",exampleSrc:"A: What time does your alarm clock ring?\nB: At six. Every morning.\nA: That is early. My alarm clock is set to seven.\nB: You are lucky. I get up at six.",funFact:"Der Wecker is the enemy of every Monday morning. 'Wecker überhören' (to sleep through the alarm) is every German's nightmare. Some people have multiple Wecker. The word Wecker also means someone who wakes you up."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Schlaf",src:"the sleep",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Same root as English 'sleep.' 'Guten Schlaf!' = Sleep well.\nSchlafzimmer (bedroom), Mittagsschlaf (afternoon nap).",example:"A: Wie war dein Schlaf letzte Nacht?\nB: Schlecht. Ich habe nur vier Stunden geschlafen.\nA: Das ist zu wenig. Schlaf ist wichtig.\nB: Ja, heute Abend wird früh ins Bett gegangen.",exampleSrc:"A: How was your sleep last night?\nB: Bad. I only slept four hours.\nA: That is too little. Sleep is important.\nB: Yes, tonight I will go to bed early.",funFact:"Germans value their Schlaf. 'Mittagsschlaf' (afternoon nap) is a tradition, especially on Sundays. 'Schlaf gut!' (sleep well) is the standard German goodnight. A Schlafmütze (sleeping cap) is a sleepyhead."},
{type:"fb",s:"Nach dem Feierabend liege ich auf der {1}.",a:["Couch"],opts:["Couch","Vase","Kabine","Stiege"],hint:"The piece of furniture you relax on at home after work.",sSrc:"After work I lie on the couch."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist 'der Wecker'?",opts:["the sleep","the alarm clock","the oven","the roof"],ans:"the alarm clock",hint:"It comes from 'wecken' (to wake) and rings every morning."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Fleck",src:"the spot, the stain",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Ein Fleck auf dem Hemd' = a stain on the shirt.\n'Blinder Fleck' = blind spot.",example:"A: Da ist ein Fleck auf dem Teppich!\nB: Oh nein. Kaffee? Der wurde wahrscheinlich verschüttet.\nA: Der Fleck muss gereinigt werden.\nB: Der Hausmeister wird informiert.",exampleSrc:"A: There is a stain on the carpet!\nB: Oh no. Coffee? It was probably spilled.\nA: The stain needs to be cleaned.\nB: The caretaker will be informed.",funFact:"'Am rechten Fleck' (in the right spot) means in the right place. 'Das Herz auf dem rechten Fleck haben' means to have your heart in the right place, to be a good person."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Nadel",src:"the needle, the pin",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Die Nadel im Heuhaufen suchen' = looking for a needle in a haystack.\nNähnadel (sewing needle), Stecknadel (pin).",example:"A: Hast du eine Nadel? Der Knopf ist abgefallen.\nB: Ja, eine Nadel und Faden.\nA: Danke. Der Knopf wird schnell wieder angenäht.\nB: Wie praktisch!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a needle? The button fell off.\nB: Yes, a needle and thread.\nA: Thanks. The button will be quickly sewn back on.\nB: How practical!",funFact:"'Die Nadel im Heuhaufen suchen' (looking for a needle in a haystack) exists in German too. Nadelwald (needle forest) is a coniferous forest. Tannennadeln (fir needles) cover the forest floor."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Nagel",src:"the nail",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Both the hardware nail and fingernail.\n'Den Nagel auf den Kopf treffen' = to hit the nail on the head.",example:"A: Ich brauche einen Nagel für das Bild.\nB: Der Hammer liegt im Werkzeugkasten.\nA: Danke. Der Nagel wird jetzt in die Wand geschlagen.\nB: Aber nicht zu laut! Es wird noch gearbeitet.",exampleSrc:"A: I need a nail for the picture.\nB: The hammer is in the toolbox.\nA: Thanks. The nail will now be hammered into the wall.\nB: But not too loud! People are still working.",funFact:"'Den Nagel auf den Kopf treffen' (to hit the nail on the head) means to be exactly right. 'Nägel mit Köpfen machen' (to make nails with heads) means to do things properly, thoroughly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Hausmeisterin",src:"the caretaker (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine form of Hausmeister. Hausmeister + -in.\nIncreasingly common in German buildings.",example:"A: Die Hausmeisterin hat den Schlüssel.\nB: Wo finde ich die Hausmeisterin?\nA: Im Erdgeschoss. Sie wurde letzte Woche eingestellt.\nB: Gut, ich gehe zu ihr.",exampleSrc:"A: The caretaker has the key.\nB: Where do I find the caretaker?\nA: On the ground floor. She was hired last week.\nB: Good, I will go to her.",funFact:"More and more German buildings have a Hausmeisterin instead of a Hausmeister. The job has become increasingly professionalized. A Hausverwaltung (building management company) often employs the Hausmeister/in."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Fleck",src:"the stain"},{trg:"die Nadel",src:"the needle"},{trg:"der Nagel",src:"the nail"},{trg:"die Hausmeisterin",src:"the caretaker (f)"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"'Da ist ein ___ auf dem Teppich!' Was fehlt?",opts:["Nagel (nein)","Ofen","Dach","Fleck"],ans:"Fleck",hint:"Something was spilled on the carpet, leaving a visible mark.",sSrc:"There is a ___ on the carpet!"},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich brauche einen {1} für das Bild an der Wand.",a:["Nagel"],opts:["Nagel","Nadel","Fleck","Wecker"],hint:"A small metal piece hammered into a wall to hang pictures.",sSrc:"I need a nail for the picture on the wall."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"das Treppenhaus",src:"the stairwell"},{trg:"das Dach",src:"the roof"},{trg:"der Bau",src:"the construction"},{trg:"das Schaufenster",src:"the shop window"},{trg:"der Korridor",src:"the corridor"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Fleck'?",opts:["the needle","the nail","the spot, the stain","the alarm clock"],ans:"the spot, the stain",hint:"Something unwanted that lands on fabric, carpet, or a surface and needs cleaning."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Wort ist KEIN österreichisches Synonym?",opts:["der Lift","die Stiege","der Korridor","der Fauteuil (nein)"],ans:"der Korridor",hint:"Three of these are specifically Austrian variants. One is used across all German-speaking regions."}
]},

// ─── Lesson 9: Anleitungen und Abläufe ───
{id:"deu_r14l14",title:"Anleitungen und Abläufe",icon:"📋",xp:10,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Anleitungen und Abläufe",desc:"Every German office runs on instructions, processes, and the sacred Betriebsrat. Learn the verbs and nouns of workplace operations: from reading manuals to resolving problems, from connecting cables to getting promoted.",goals:["Learn workplace process vocabulary (Anleitung, Betriebsrat, Abonnement)","Master action verbs for office operations (anschließen, ausfallen, einfügen)","Understand Feierabend culture and the Arbeitszeitgesetz"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"amused",art:"de-ber-office-evening",trg:"Um 17:01 ist das Büro leer. Kein Mensch. Kein Geräusch. Nur der Kopierer blinkt noch im Flur, weil ihn niemand ausgeschaltet hat.",src:"At 5:01 PM the office is empty. Not a soul. Not a sound. Only the copier still blinks in the hallway, because nobody turned it off."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Abonnement",src:"the subscription",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From French 'abonner.' Germans love their Abos (abbreviation).\nStreaming, gym, magazines: everything runs on Abonnements.",example:"A: Hast du ein Abonnement für die Zeitung?\nB: Ja, ein digitales Abonnement. Wird monatlich bezahlt.\nA: Und das Fitnessstudio?\nB: Auch ein Abonnement. Zwölf Monate.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a subscription for the newspaper?\nB: Yes, a digital subscription. It is paid monthly.\nA: And the gym?\nB: Also a subscription. Twelve months.",funFact:"Germans love their Abos. A typical German household has Abonnements for: newspaper, streaming, phone, public transit, gym, and magazine. 'Abo kündigen' (cancel subscription) is a common internet search."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Anleitung",src:"the instructions, the guide",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"An- (to) + Leitung (guidance). 'Schritt-für-Schritt-Anleitung.'\nEvery IKEA furniture comes with a wordless Anleitung.",example:"A: Wo ist die Anleitung für den Drucker?\nB: Die Anleitung wurde online hochgeladen.\nA: Gut. Ich lese sie mir durch.\nB: Die Anleitung ist auf Deutsch und Englisch.",exampleSrc:"A: Where are the instructions for the printer?\nB: The instructions were uploaded online.\nA: Good. I will read through them.\nB: The instructions are in German and English.",funFact:"Every IKEA furniture comes with a wordless Anleitung. Germans actually read their Anleitungen before assembling anything. 'Ohne Anleitung aufbauen' (to assemble without instructions) is considered reckless."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Bedienungsanleitung",src:"the user manual, the operating instructions",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Bedienung (operation) + Anleitung (instructions).\nGermans actually READ their Bedienungsanleitungen.",example:"A: Wo ist die Bedienungsanleitung für den Kopierer?\nB: Im Ordner neben dem Regal.\nA: Die Bedienungsanleitung hat dreißig Seiten!\nB: Ja, aber sie wurde übersichtlich geschrieben.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the user manual for the copier?\nB: In the binder next to the shelf.\nA: The user manual has thirty pages!\nB: Yes, but it was written clearly.",funFact:"Bedienungsanleitung is one of the longest common compound words in German office life. Germans actually read their Bedienungsanleitungen. In other countries, they are famously ignored."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Gebrauchsanweisung",src:"the instructions for use",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Gebrauch (use) + Anweisung (instruction). More formal.\nFound on medicine, cleaning products, and technical equipment.",example:"A: Steht in der Gebrauchsanweisung, wie man das reinigt?\nB: Ja, auf Seite drei. Es wurde genau beschrieben.\nA: Gut, dann lese ich die Gebrauchsanweisung.\nB: Die Gebrauchsanweisung ist auch online verfügbar.",exampleSrc:"A: Does the instructions for use say how to clean it?\nB: Yes, on page three. It was described exactly.\nA: Good, then I will read the instructions.\nB: The instructions for use are also available online.",funFact:"Gebrauchsanweisung is the formal version of Bedienungsanleitung. Medicine always has a Gebrauchsanweisung (also called Beipackzettel). Reading the Gebrauchsanweisung before using medication is a German habit."},
{type:"mc",q:"What is the difference between 'Anleitung' and 'Gebrauchsanweisung'?",opts:["Anleitung is used only for cooking recipes and instructions","They mean completely different things in most contexts","Gebrauchsanweisung is more formal, found on medicine and technical products","Gebrauchsanweisung is informal slang used online"],ans:"Gebrauchsanweisung is more formal, found on medicine and technical products",hint:"Both mean instructions. One is the casual everyday word. The other is the official, regulated term printed in product packaging for complex devices and drugs."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Betriebsrat",src:"the works council",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Betrieb (company) + Rat (council). A legally mandated employee body.\nHas real power: hiring, firing, working conditions.",example:"A: Was macht der Betriebsrat?\nB: Er vertritt die Interessen der Mitarbeiter.\nA: Und er wird von den Mitarbeitern gewählt?\nB: Ja, alle vier Jahre. Die Wahl wird geheim durchgeführt.",exampleSrc:"A: What does the works council do?\nB: It represents the interests of the employees.\nA: And it is elected by the employees?\nB: Yes, every four years. The election is conducted secretly.",funFact:"The Betriebsrat is a legally mandated employee representation body in German companies with 5+ employees. It has real power over hiring, firing, and working conditions. It is a uniquely German form of workplace democracy."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mobilbox",src:"the voicemail box",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Mobil (mobile) + Box. Your mobile phone voicemail.\nAlso called 'Mailbox' in German.",example:"A: Ich habe dich angerufen, aber du warst nicht da.\nB: Hast du auf die Mobilbox gesprochen?\nA: Ja, eine Nachricht wurde hinterlassen.\nB: Ich höre sie gleich ab.",exampleSrc:"A: I called you, but you were not there.\nB: Did you speak on the voicemail?\nA: Yes, a message was left.\nB: I will listen to it right away.",funFact:"Germans call voicemail 'Mobilbox' or 'Mailbox.' 'Bitte hinterlassen Sie eine Nachricht nach dem Signalton' (please leave a message after the beep) is the standard German voicemail greeting."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mobilität",src:"the mobility",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Elektromobilität' is a huge topic in Germany.\nThe -ität ending is always feminine.",example:"A: Mobilität ist wichtig für den Job.\nB: Ja, flexible Mobilität wird erwartet.\nA: Wird ein Firmenwagen zur Verfügung gestellt?\nB: Nein, aber ein Jobticket für den Nahverkehr.",exampleSrc:"A: Mobility is important for the job.\nB: Yes, flexible mobility is expected.\nA: Is a company car provided?\nB: No, but a job ticket for public transport.",funFact:"The -ität ending is always feminine and matches English -ity: Mobilität, Qualität, Aktivität, Universität. A free gender rule for hundreds of German nouns."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"das Abonnement",src:"the subscription"},{trg:"die Anleitung",src:"the instructions"},{trg:"der Betriebsrat",src:"the works council"},{trg:"die Mobilbox",src:"the voicemail box"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"anschließen",src:"to connect, to plug in",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"An- (to/on) + schließen (to close/connect).\n'Den Monitor anschließen' = to connect the monitor.",example:"A: Wie schließe ich den Monitor an?\nB: Das Kabel wird hinten angeschlossen.\nA: Welches Kabel?\nB: Das HDMI-Kabel. Es wurde gestern bestellt.",exampleSrc:"A: How do I connect the monitor?\nB: The cable is connected in the back.\nA: Which cable?\nB: The HDMI cable. It was ordered yesterday.",funFact:"Anschließen means to connect or join. 'Sich jemandem anschließen' means to join someone. 'Im Anschluss an' means following/after. One verb, many connections."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ausfallen",src:"to fail, to be cancelled, to break down",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Aus- (out) + fallen (to fall). 'Der Strom fällt aus' = power outage.\n'Die Besprechung fällt aus' = the meeting is cancelled.",example:"A: Die Besprechung fällt heute aus.\nB: Warum? Was ist ausgefallen?\nA: Der Strom ist ausgefallen.\nB: Wann wird der Strom wieder eingeschaltet?",exampleSrc:"A: The meeting is cancelled today.\nB: Why? What failed?\nA: The power went out.\nB: When will the power be turned back on?",funFact:"Ausfallen is a versatile word for things going wrong. Stromausfall (power failure), Haarausfall (hair loss), Unterrichtsausfall (class cancellation). When something ausfällt, it literally falls out of existence."},
{type:"teach",trg:"auflösen",src:"to dissolve, to resolve, to disband",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Auf- (up/open) + lösen (to solve/loosen). 'Ein Rätsel auflösen.'\nAlso: 'Einen Vertrag auflösen' = to terminate a contract.",example:"A: Das Problem wurde endlich aufgelöst.\nB: Wie?\nA: Der Fehler wurde im System gefunden und behoben.\nB: Gut. Dann kann die Abteilung normal weiterarbeiten.",exampleSrc:"A: The problem was finally resolved.\nB: How?\nA: The error was found in the system and fixed.\nB: Good. Then the department can continue working normally.",funFact:"Auflösen works for physical (dissolving sugar), organizational (disbanding a team), and intellectual (solving a riddle) dissolution. 'Die Auflösung' at the end of a mystery is the reveal."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einfügen",src:"to insert, to paste",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ein- (in) + fügen (to fit). 'Text einfügen' = to paste text.\nCtrl+V in German is 'Einfügen.'",example:"A: Kannst du den Text hier einfügen?\nB: Ja, er wird sofort eingefügt.\nA: Der Text wurde von der Leiterin geschrieben.\nB: Gut, ich füge ihn in das Dokument ein.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you insert the text here?\nB: Yes, it will be inserted right away.\nA: The text was written by the manager.\nB: Good, I will insert it into the document.",funFact:"In German computer menus, 'Einfügen' is the paste command (Ctrl+V). 'Sich einfügen' means to fit in, to integrate. New employees must 'sich ins Team einfügen' (fit into the team)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"herausfinden",src:"to find out, to discover",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Heraus- (out) + finden (to find). Separable verb.\n'Ich muss herausfinden, wann Feierabend ist.'",example:"A: Hast du herausgefunden, wann die Konferenz ist?\nB: Ja, nächsten Dienstag. Es wurde gestern festgelegt.\nA: Gut. Ich muss noch herausfinden, wer teilnimmt.\nB: Das wird von der Sekretärin organisiert.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you find out when the conference is?\nB: Yes, next Tuesday. It was determined yesterday.\nA: Good. I still need to find out who is participating.\nB: That is being organized by the secretary.",funFact:"Herausfinden is the detective verb of German. You find things out, you discover them. 'Es stellte sich heraus' (it turned out) is used when discoveries are made. Every good Krimi (crime novel) is about herausfinden."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Besprechung {1} heute aus, weil der Strom ausgefallen ist.",a:["fällt"],opts:["fällt","fallen","fiel","gefallen"],hint:"The meeting IS cancelled (present tense, 3rd person singular).",sSrc:"The meeting is cancelled today because the power went out."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'einfügen' am Computer?",opts:["to delete","to save","to print","to paste"],ans:"to paste",hint:"This is the German word for the Ctrl+V keyboard shortcut."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Problem wurde endlich {1}.",a:"aufgelöst",opts:["aufgelöst","eingefügt","ausgefallen","angeschlossen"],hint:"A separable verb meaning to resolve, dissolve, or disband.",sSrc:"The problem was finally resolved."}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Alltag und Feierabend ───
{id:"deu_r14l15",title:"Alltag und Feierabend",icon:"🌇",xp:10,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Alltag und Feierabend",desc:"From washing dishes to vacuuming, from tweeting to getting promoted: the verbs of everyday office and home life, plus the sacred German concept of Feierabend.",goals:["Learn everyday action verbs (abwaschen, staubsaugen, befördern)","Understand Feierabend culture and the Arbeitszeitgesetz","Master orientation adjectives (waagerecht, senkrecht, innerhalb)"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"abwaschen",src:"to wash dishes, to wash off",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ab- (off) + waschen (to wash). 'Den Abwasch machen' = to do the dishes.\nIn the Kaffeküche: the eternal question, who does the Abwasch?",example:"A: Wer wäscht heute in der Kaffeküche ab?\nB: Du bist dran. Es steht auf dem Reinigungsplan.\nA: Aber gestern wurde auch schon von mir abgewaschen!\nB: Das stimmt nicht. Gestern wurde von Thomas abgewaschen.",exampleSrc:"A: Who does the dishes in the coffee kitchen today?\nB: You are up. It is on the cleaning schedule.\nA: But yesterday I also did the dishes!\nB: That is not true. Yesterday Thomas did the dishes.",funFact:"In the Kaffeküche, the eternal question is: who does the Abwasch? The Reinigungsplan (cleaning schedule) is supposed to solve this, but passive-aggressive notes suggest it does not always work."},
{type:"teach",trg:"staubsaugen",src:"to vacuum",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Staub (dust) + saugen (to suck). 'Dust-sucking.'\nAlso written as two words: 'Staub saugen.'",example:"A: Wer saugt heute Staub im Büro?\nB: Der Hausmeister. Es wird jeden Freitag gestaubsaugt.\nA: Gut. Der Teppich muss dringend gesaugt werden.\nB: Ja, es wurde schon lange nicht mehr gestaubsaugt.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is vacuuming in the office today?\nB: The caretaker. It is vacuumed every Friday.\nA: Good. The carpet urgently needs to be vacuumed.\nB: Yes, it has not been vacuumed in a long time.",funFact:"Staubsauger (vacuum cleaner) literally means 'dust sucker.' Germans debate whether the past participle is 'gestaubsaugt' or 'staubgesaugt.' Both exist. It is one of German's great grammar controversies."},
{type:"teach",trg:"twittern",src:"to tweet, to post on social media",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From English 'Twitter.' Adapted with German verb ending.\nUsed broadly for short social media posts.",example:"A: Hat der Betrieb einen Social-Media-Account?\nB: Ja, es wird jeden Tag getwittert.\nA: Wer twittert für den Betrieb?\nB: Die Marketing-Abteilung. Alles wird vorher geprüft.",exampleSrc:"A: Does the company have a social media account?\nB: Yes, tweets are posted every day.\nA: Who tweets for the company?\nB: The marketing department. Everything is checked beforehand.",funFact:"German happily adopts English tech verbs and adds German grammar: twittern, googeln, liken, chatten, bloggen. They conjugate fully: ich twittere, du twitterst, er twittert, wir haben getwittert."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'staubsaugen'?",opts:["to sweep up","to vacuum","to dust off","to mop up"],ans:"to vacuum",hint:"Staub (dust) + saugen (to suck). Literally 'dust-sucking.' Done every Friday by the Hausmeister."},
{type:"teach",trg:"elektronisch",src:"electronic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Elektronische Post' = email (formal term).\n'Elektronische Geräte' = electronic devices.",example:"A: Ist das Formular elektronisch oder auf Papier?\nB: Elektronisch. Es wird digital ausgefüllt.\nA: Gut. Elektronische Dokumente werden schneller bearbeitet.\nB: Ja, die Digitalisierung hilft.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the form electronic or on paper?\nB: Electronic. It is filled out digitally.\nA: Good. Electronic documents are processed faster.\nB: Yes, digitalization helps.",funFact:"'Elektronische Post' is the formal German term for email. Nobody uses it in conversation (everyone says E-Mail), but it appears on government forms. German bureaucracy loves formal terms for modern technology."},
{type:"teach",trg:"waagerecht",src:"horizontal",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Waage (scale/balance) + recht (right/straight).\nOpposite: senkrecht (vertical). Used in crossword puzzles.",example:"A: Hängt das Regal waagerecht?\nB: Nein, es hängt etwas schief.\nA: Es muss waagerecht ausgerichtet werden.\nB: Ich brauche eine Wasserwaage.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the shelf hanging horizontally?\nB: No, it is hanging a bit crooked.\nA: It needs to be aligned horizontally.\nB: I need a spirit level.",funFact:"Waagerecht and senkrecht are the German crossword puzzle words: waagerecht = across, senkrecht = down. A Wasserwaage (water scale = spirit level) checks if something is perfectly waagerecht."},
{type:"teach",trg:"waagrecht",src:"horizontal (variant)",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Shorter variant of waagerecht. Both are correct.\nMore common in Austrian and Swiss German.",example:"A: Ist die Linie waagrecht?\nB: Ja, perfekt waagrecht.\nA: Waagrecht und waagerecht sind beide richtig?\nB: Ja, waagrecht ist die kürzere Form.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the line horizontal?\nB: Yes, perfectly horizontal.\nA: Waagrecht and waagerecht are both correct?\nB: Yes, waagrecht is the shorter form.",funFact:"Waagrecht is the shorter variant of waagerecht. Both are correct. Austrian German prefers waagrecht. The Goethe exam accepts both spellings."},
{type:"teach",trg:"innerhalb",src:"within, inside of",pos:"prep",gender:null,note:"Inner (inside) + halb (half/side). Takes Genitiv.\n'Innerhalb einer Woche' = within a week.",example:"A: Innerhalb des Betriebs gelten besondere Regeln.\nB: Welche Regeln?\nA: Zum Beispiel: Überstunden werden innerhalb eines Monats ausgeglichen.\nB: Das ist eine gute Regelung.",exampleSrc:"A: Within the company, special rules apply.\nB: Which rules?\nA: For example: overtime is compensated within a month.\nB: That is a good regulation.",funFact:"Innerhalb takes Genitiv: innerhalb des Gebäudes (within the building), innerhalb einer Woche (within a week). Its opposite is außerhalb (outside of). Both are essential for describing rules and boundaries."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"anschließen",src:"to connect"},{trg:"ausfallen",src:"to fail, to cancel"},{trg:"einfügen",src:"to insert, to paste"},{trg:"herausfinden",src:"to find out"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Kabel wird hinten {1}.",a:["angeschlossen"],opts:["angeschlossen","ausgefallen","aufgelöst","eingefügt"],hint:"The cable is being connected at the back (passive, past participle).",sSrc:"The cable is connected in the back."},
{type:"tip",title:"Feierabend: The Sacred Boundary",text:"Feierabend literally means 'celebration evening.'\nIt marks the end of work and the beginning of free time.\n\nGermans take this boundary seriously:\n- Work emails after Feierabend are frowned upon\n- Some companies block email servers after 6 PM\n- The Betriebsrat monitors compliance\n- Overtime is documented and compensated\n\nWork-life balance is not a buzzword in Germany.\nIt is a cultural value protected by law.",deepDive:{title:"The Arbeitszeitgesetz (Working Hours Act)",text:"The German Arbeitszeitgesetz regulates:\n- Maximum 8 hours per day (10 in exceptions)\n- Minimum 11 hours rest between workdays\n- Sunday and public holiday rest\n- Overtime compensation within 6 months\n\nThe Betriebsrat monitors compliance.\nViolations can be punished with fines.\n\nFeierabend is not just tradition. It is law."}},
{type:"teach",trg:"befördern",src:"to promote, to transport",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Be- + fördern (to support/advance).\n'Befördert werden' = to be promoted.",example:"A: Sie wurde zur Teamleiterin befördert.\nB: Das hat sie verdient!\nA: Wann wirst du befördert?\nB: Hoffentlich nächstes Jahr.",exampleSrc:"A: She was promoted to team leader.\nB: She deserved it!\nA: When will you be promoted?\nB: Hopefully next year.",funFact:"Befördern has two meanings: to promote (a person) and to transport (goods). Die Post befördert Briefe (the post transports letters). Der Chef befördert Mitarbeiter (the boss promotes employees)."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Überstunden werden innerhalb eines Monats ausgeglichen.' Was bedeutet 'innerhalb'?",opts:["outside of","despite","within","because of"],ans:"within",hint:"This preposition describes something happening INSIDE a time frame."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sie {1} gestern zur Teamleiterin befördert.",a:["wurde"],opts:["wurde","wird","werden","worden"],hint:"She WAS promoted (past passive, singular feminine).",sSrc:"She was promoted to team leader yesterday."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was macht der Betriebsrat?",opts:["Er kocht jeden Morgen Kaffee in der Kaffeküche","Er reinigt täglich das gesamte Treppenhaus","Er schreibt die technische Bedienungsanleitung","Er vertritt die Interessen der Mitarbeiter"],ans:"Er vertritt die Interessen der Mitarbeiter",hint:"This legally mandated body represents employee interests in the company."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"abwaschen",src:"to wash dishes"},{trg:"staubsaugen",src:"to vacuum"},{trg:"twittern",src:"to tweet"},{trg:"befördern",src:"to promote"},{trg:"elektronisch",src:"electronic"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-office-exit-sunset",trg:"Verumius verlässt das Büro. Die Sonne steht tief über Berlin. Sein erster Arbeitstag wurde gemeistert. Morgen wird er wissen, wo der Kopierer steht und wann Feierabend ist.",src:"Verumius leaves the office. The sun hangs low over Berlin. His first workday has been mastered. Tomorrow he will know where the copier is and when the workday ends."},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"friendly",art:"de-ber-street-evening",trg:"Übrigens, nächste Woche fahren wir nach Hamburg. Eine Geschäftsreise. Du brauchst einen Anzug, der passt, und einen Koffer, der nicht zu groß ist.",src:"By the way, next week we are going to Hamburg. A business trip. You need a suit that fits and a suitcase that is not too big."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der erste Arbeitstag {1} erfolgreich gemeistert.",a:["wurde"],opts:["wurde","wird","werden","worden"],hint:"The first workday WAS successfully mastered. Past passive, singular.",sSrc:"The first workday was successfully mastered."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Die Mitarbeiterin, {1} die E-Mail {2} hat, {3} gestern {4}.",blanks:{"1":"die","2":"geschrieben","3":"wurde","4":"befördert"},pool:["die","der","geschrieben","schreiben","wurde","wird","befördert","befördern"],hint:"Feminine colleague WHO wrote the email (Nominativ). She WAS promoted (Passiv Präteritum).",sSrc:"The colleague who wrote the email was promoted yesterday."},
{type:"mc",q:"Hängt das Regal ___? Nein, es hängt etwas schief.",opts:["waagerecht","senkrecht","innerhalb","elektronisch"],ans:"waagerecht",hint:"This adjective means perfectly level, the opposite of vertical."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ist die Linie {1}? Ja, perfekt horizontal.",a:"waagrecht",opts:["waagrecht","senkrecht","innerhalb","einheitlich"],hint:"The shorter Austrian/Swiss variant of horizontal. Both spellings are correct.",sSrc:"Is the line horizontal? Yes, perfectly horizontal."}
]}

]};

export default UNIT_14;
